# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2023-african-beach-games
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2023-african-beach-games/2019-african-beach-games] The **2019 African Beach Games** were the inaugural edition of the international beach sports competition between the nations of Africa, organised by the Association of National Olympic Committees of Africa (ANOCA).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/2019-african-beach-games] The first Games were held on the island of Sal, Cape Verde in June 2019.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/2019-african-beach-games] In the ten-day competition, a total of 45 nations competed in 28 events across 11 sports.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/2019-african-beach-games] Teqball was also included as a demonstration sport on 18 June.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/2019-african-beach-games] The Games were awarded to the Cabo Verdean Olympic Committee (COC) at the ANOCA General Assembly in Djibouti in May 2017.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/2019-african-beach-games] The host contract was signed in March 2018 between the City Hall of Sal, the Association of National Olympic Committees of Africa (ANOCA) and the Cabo Verdean Olympic Committee (COC), to carry out of the first African Beach Games 2019.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/2019-african-beach-games] The logo is the silhouette of the African continent, while the mascot is a tortoise named Krexteu.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/2019-african-beach-games] Chad, Comoros, Eritrea, Eswatini, Ethiopia, Gabon, São Tomé and Príncipe, Somalia and South Africa did not participate.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/2023-african-beach-games] The **2023 African Beach Games** is the 2nd edition of the international beach sports competition between the nations of Africa, organised by the Association of National Olympic Committees of Africa (ANOCA).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/2023-african-beach-games] The games were held in Hammamet, Tunisia in June 2023.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/2023-african-beach-games] A total of 1100 athletes from 53 nations competed in 30 events across 16 sports.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Africa straddles the equator and the prime meridian.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The continent is surrounded by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, the Arabian plate and the Gulf of Aqaba to the northeast, the Indian Ocean to the southeast and the Atlantic Ocean to the west.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] France, Italy, Portugal, Spain, and Yemen have parts of their territories located on African geographical soil, mostly in the form of islands.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The continent includes Madagascar and various archipelagos.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] It contains 54 fully recognised sovereign states, eight cities and islands that are part of non-African states, and two *de facto* independent states with limited or no recognition.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] This count does not include Malta and Sicily, which are geologically part of the African continent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Algeria is Africa's largest country by area, and Nigeria is its largest by population.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] African nations cooperate through the establishment of the African Union, which is headquartered in Addis Ababa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Africa is highly biodiverse; it is the continent with the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] However, Africa is also heavily affected by a wide range of environmental issues, including desertification, deforestation, water scarcity, and pollution.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] These entrenched environmental concerns are expected to worsen as climate change impacts Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change has identified Africa as the continent most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The history of Africa is long, complex, and varied, and has often been under-appreciated by the global historical community.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In African societies the oral word is revered, and they have generally recorded their history via oral tradition, which has led anthropologists to term them "oral civilisations", contrasted with "literate civilisations" which pride the written word.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] African culture is rich and diverse both within and between the continent's regions, encompassing art, cuisine, music and dance, religion, and dress.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Africa, particularly Eastern Africa, is widely accepted to be the place of origin of humans and the Hominidae clade, also known as the great apes.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The earliest hominids and their ancestors have been dated to around 7 million years ago, and *Homo sapiens* (modern human) are believed to have originated in Africa 350,000 to 260,000 years ago.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Throughout history the continent saw the rise and fall of many kingdoms and empires, such as Ancient Egypt, Makuria, the Fatimids, Mali, the Asante, Kongo, the Luba, Bunyoro, Great Zimbabwe, Imerina, and the Zulu.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Despite the predominance of states, many societies were heterarchical and stateless.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Slave trades created various diasporas, especially in the Americas.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] From the late-19th century to early 20th century, driven by the Second Industrial Revolution, most of Africa was rapidly conquered and colonised by European nations, save for Ethiopia and Liberia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] European rule had significant impacts on Africa's societies, and colonies were maintained for the purpose of economic exploitation and extraction of natural resources.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Most present states emerged from a process of decolonisation following World War II, and established the Organisation of African Unity in 1963, the predecessor to the African Union.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The nascent countries decided to keep their colonial borders, with traditional power structures used in governance to varying degrees.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Under Roman rule, Carthage became the capital of the province then named *Africa Proconsularis*, following the Roman victory over the Carthaginians in the Third Punic War in 146 BC, which also included the coastal part of modern Libya.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Latin suffix *-ica* can sometimes be used to denote a land (e.g., in *Celtica* from *Celtae*, as used by Julius Caesar).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The later Muslim region of Ifriqiya, following its conquest of the Byzantine (Eastern Roman) Empire's *Exarchatus Africae*, also preserved a form of the name.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] According to the Romans, Africa lies to the west of Egypt, while "Asia" was used to refer to Anatolia and lands to the east.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] A definite line was drawn between the two continents by the geographer Ptolemy (85–165 CE), indicating Alexandria along the Prime Meridian and making the isthmus of Suez and the Red Sea the boundary between Asia and Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] As Europeans came to understand the real extent of the continent, the idea of "Africa" expanded with their knowledge.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In accordance with African cosmology, African historical consciousness viewed historical change and continuity, order and purpose within the framework of man and his environment, the gods, and his ancestors, and he believed himself part of a holistic spiritual entity.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In African societies, the historical process is largely a communal one, with eyewitness accounts, hearsay, reminiscences, and occasionally visions, dreams, and hallucinations crafted into narrative oral traditions which are performed and transmitted through generations.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In oral traditions time is sometimes mythical and social, and ancestors were considered historical actors.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Mind and memory shapes traditions, as events are condensed over time and crystallise into clichés.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Oral tradition can be exoteric or esoteric.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] It speaks to people according to their understanding, unveiling itself in accordance with their aptitudes.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Africa is considered by most paleoanthropologists to be the oldest inhabited territory on Earth, with the Human species originating from the continent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] During the mid-20th century, anthropologists discovered many fossils and evidence of human occupation perhaps as early as seven million years ago ("Before Present"; BP).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Fossil remains of several species of early apelike humans thought to have evolved into modern humans, such as *Australopithecus afarensis* radiometrically dated to approximately 3.9–3.0 million years BP, *Paranthropus boisei* (c.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] 2.3–1.4 million years BP) and *Homo ergaster* (c.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] 1.9 million–600,000 years BP) have been discovered.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] After the evolution of *Homo sapiens* approximately 350,000 to 260,000 years BP in Africa, the continent was mainly populated by groups of hunter-gatherers.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] These first modern humans left Africa and populated the rest of the globe during the Out of Africa II migration dated to approximately 50,000 years BP, exiting the continent either across Bab-el-Mandeb over the Red Sea, the Strait of Gibraltar in Morocco, or the Isthmus of Suez in Egypt.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Other migrations of modern humans within the African continent have been dated to that time, with evidence of early human settlement found in Southern Africa, Southeast Africa, North Africa, and the Sahara.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] However, the warming and drying climate meant that by 5,000 BC, the Sahara region was becoming increasingly dry and hostile.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Around 3500 BC, due to a tilt in the Earth's orbit, the Sahara experienced a period of rapid desertification.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The domestication of cattle in Africa preceded agriculture and seems to have existed alongside hunter-gatherer cultures.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] It is speculated that by 6,000 BC, cattle were domesticated in North Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In West Africa, a wet phase ushered in an expanding rainforest and wooded savanna from Senegal to Cameroon.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Between 9,000 and 5,000 BC, Niger–Congo speakers domesticated the oil palm and raffia palm.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Black-eyed peas and voandzeia (African groundnuts), were domesticated, followed by okra and kola nuts.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Since most of the plants grew in the forest, the Niger–Congo speakers invented polished stone axes for clearing forest.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Pygmies are thought to have inhabited Central Africa for many millennia, splitting into eastern and western groups around 5,000 BP.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Over 150,000 BP, there was an early dispersal of anatomically modern humans to Southern Africa, equated with the modern-day Khoisan who have preserved their traditional hunter-gatherer way of life.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] From 3500 BC, nomes (ruled by nomarchs) coalesced to form the kingdoms of Lower Egypt and Upper Egypt in northeast Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Around 3100 BC Upper Egypt conquered Lower Egypt to unify Egypt under the 1st dynasty, with the process of consolidation and assimilation completed by the time of the 3rd dynasty who formed the Old Kingdom of Egypt in 2686 BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Kingdom of Kerma emerged around this time to become the dominant force in Nubia, controlling territory as large as Egypt between the 1st and 4th cataracts of the Nile.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The height of the Old Kingdom saw the construction of many great pyramids, though under the 6th dynasty power gradually decentralised to the nomarchs, culminating in the disintegration of the kingdom, exacerbated by drought and famine.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Around 2055 BC, the 11th dynasty, based in Thebes, conquered the others to form the Middle Kingdom of Egypt, and the 12th dynasty expanded into Lower Nubia at the expense of Kerma.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Around 1700 BC, the Middle Kingdom fractured in two, and the Hyksos (a militaristic people from Palestine) invaded and conquered Lower Egypt, while Kerma coordinated invasions deep into Egypt to reach its greatest extent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In 1550 BC, the 18th dynasty expelled the Hyksos, and established the New Kingdom of Egypt.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The New Kingdom conquered the Levant from the Canaanites, Mittani, Amorites, and Hittites, and extinguished Kerma, incorporating Nubia into the empire, and sending the Egyptian empire into its golden age.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Internal struggles, drought, famine, and invasions by a confederation of seafaring peoples contributed to the New Kingdom's collapse in 1069 BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The New Kingdom's collapse liberated the Kingdom of Kush in Nubia, which manoeuvred into power in Upper Egypt and conquered Lower Egypt in 754 BC to form the Kushite Empire.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Kushites ruled for a century and oversaw a revival in pyramid building, until they were driven out of Egypt by the Assyrians in 663 BC in reprisal for their expansion towards the Assyrian Empire.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Assyrians installed a puppet dynasty that later gained independence and once more unified Egypt, until it was conquered by the Achaemenid Empire in 525 BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Egypt briefly regained independence from the Achaemenids under the 28th dynasty from 404 to 343 BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The conquest of Achaemenid Egypt by Alexander the Great in 332 BC marked the beginning of Hellenistic rule and the installation of the Macedonian Ptolemaic dynasty in Egypt.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Ptolemaics lost their holdings outside of Africa to the Seleucids in the Syrian Wars, expanded into Cyrenaica, and briefly occupied part of Kush in the 3rd century BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 1st century BC, Ptolemaic Egypt became entangled in a Roman civil war, leading to its conquest by the Romans in 30 BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Kush persisted as a major regional power until, having been weakened from internal rebellion amid worsening climatic conditions, invasions by Aksum and the Noba caused their disintegration into Makuria, Alodia, and Nobatia around the 5th century AD.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, there was the Land of Punt, a kingdom on the Red Sea which was a close trading partner of Ancient Egypt in the 3rd and 2nd millennia BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Rodolfo Fattovich equated it to the Gash Group in the Sudanese-Eritrean lowlands, and some scholars have hypothesised modern-day Somalia, while Kenneth Kitchen and Felix Chami locate it on Zanzibar Island.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the Eritrean-Ethiopian Highlands, the kingdom of dʿmt rose c.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] 980 BC as the region was incorporated into global trading networks, and it exhibited Sabaean influences which most scholars attribute to a small migration of Sabaeans and their assimilation.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Several scholars consider there to have been other contemporaneous states, and dʿmt's collapse in the mid-1st century BC saw the region inhabited by small polities.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Modern-day Somalia was inhabited by nomadic pastoralists, and along the Horn's coast there were many ancient Somali city-states that thrived off of the wider Red Sea trade, and enjoyed a lucrative monopoly on cinnamon from Ancient India due to their freedom from Roman interference.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 1st century AD, the Kingdom of Aksum rose from a city-state to rule much of the northern Ethiopian-Eritrean Highlands and the Red Sea port of Adulis.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Aksum was described as one of the four great powers by Persian prophet Mani in the 3rd century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Aksum's king converted from traditional religion to Christianity in the 4th century, gradually followed by the population.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 6th century, Aksum conquered South Arabia, though struggled to maintain control over it, and began to gradually lose its dominance over Red Sea trade to Persians and Arabs.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Northwest Africa (the Maghreb) was inhabited by Berber semi-nomadic pastoralists.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 1st millennium BC, Phoenician migration and settlement came in search for precious metals in the Gulf of Tunis.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] This grew into Ancient Carthage after gaining independence from Phoenicia in the 6th century BC, and they built an extensive trading empire with a strict mercantile network.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Carthage's collapse and conquest by Rome in the Punic Wars (3rd and 2nd centuries BC) saw Numidia and Mauretania become major powers in the Maghreb.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 2nd century BC Mauretania fought alongside Numidia's Jugurtha against the Romans in the Jugurthine War after he had usurped the Numidian throne from a Roman ally.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Together they inflicted heavy casualties, with the war only ending inconclusively when Mauretania's Bocchus I sold out Jugurtha to the Romans.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, both came under direct Roman rule.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] While traditional religion predominated among Berbers, some people converted to Christianity.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 5th century AD the Vandals conquered Roman Africa before the fall of Rome, though the province was reconquered by the Byzantines a century later.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Large swathes of indigenous peoples regained self-governance in Masuna and its numerous successor polities in the Maghreb, including the kingdoms of Ouarsenis, Aurès, and Altava.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the western Sahel the rise of settled communities occurred largely as a result of the domestication of millet and of sorghum, and cattle pastoralism began c.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Extensive east-west belts of deserts, grasslands, and forests from north to south were crucial for the moulding of their respective societies and meant that symbiotic trade relations developed in response to the differing environments.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Beginning around 4000 BC, the Tichitt culture in modern-day Mauritania and Mali is the oldest known complexly organised society in West Africa, while others included the Kintampo culture in modern-day Ghana, the Nok culture in modern-day Nigeria, and the Daima culture around Lake Chad.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Towards the end of the 3rd century AD, a wet period in the Sahel created areas for human habitation and exploitation that had not been habitable for the best part of a millennium.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Ghana Empire (also called *Wagadu*) rose out of the Tichitt culture, growing wealthy following the introduction of the camel to the western Sahel, which revolutionised the trans-Saharan trade that linked their capital and Aoudaghost with Tahert and Sijilmasa in North Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Soninke tradition holds that the final founding of Wagadu occurred after Dinga did a deal with Bida, a serpent deity who was guarding a well, to sacrifice one maiden a year in exchange for assurance regarding plenty of rainfall and gold supply.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Based on large tumuli scattered across West Africa dating to this period, several scholars have speculated that there were further simultaneous and preceding states relative to Wagadu.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the Grasslands of northwestern Cameroon, Bantu-speaking agriculturalists started to gradually migrate south sometime between 5000 BC and 3000 BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Despite intensive research, the cause of the migrations, and that of the directions taken, is still unclear, however there is consensus that there were multiple dispersal events.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Around 1500 BC, Bantu speakers reached central Cameroon.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The 'Western Stream' likely followed the coast and the major rivers of the Congo system southwards to reach the southern fringe of the Congolian Rainforest around 500 BC (some may have used the sea to circumvent the rainforest).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Their arrival coincided with the spread of iron metallurgy through Central Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Meanwhile, the 'Eastern Stream' travelled either the northern fringe of the rainforest or the Ubangi River eastwards, and reached just west of Lake Victoria around 500 BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] While there, Bantu speakers adopted iron metallurgy from Cushitic speakers already present, and coexisted with them.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Dispersal from the Great Lakes region occurred in two more streams.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] One went west to meet the Western Stream in the DR Congo and Angola, while the other went south and spread across Eastern and Southern Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Around the turn of the millennium, Bantu speakers reached central modern-day Tanzania and near Dar es Salaam, before rapidly moving southwards along the coast to reach modern-day Kwazulu Natal in South Africa around the 3rd century AD.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Throughout this, Bantu speakers displaced, replaced, or intermarried with and absorbed hunter-gatherer and agricultural groups.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 7th and 8th centuries, as part of the Arab conquests which sought to spread Islamic rule, the Rashidun and Umayyad caliphates conquered North Africa at the expense of the Byzantine Empire and Berber leaders such as Kusaila and Kahina.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Large numbers of Berber and Coptic people willingly converted to Islam, and followers of Abrahamic religions ('People of the Book') were protected, though followers of Berber traditional religion were violently oppressed.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 8th century the Berber Revolt rocked the Caliphate and Berber dynasties took control over the Maghreb, while the Tulunids briefly controlled Egypt.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 10th century, the Fatimids rose to power in modern-day Tunisia, established a rival caliphate, and conquered Egypt, before expanding into the Middle East.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 11th century the Almoravids conquered the Maghreb and intervened in the Christian reconquest of Iberia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Saladin, a Fatimid vizier, usurped power in the 12th century and established the Ayyubid dynasty which restored Egyptian prestige, while the Almohad revolution deposed the Almoravids to the east.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] After Christian gains in Iberia in the 13th century, the Almohads disintegrated into the Marinids, Zayyanids, and Hafsids in modern-day Morocco, Algeria, and Tunisia respectively.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the face of Mongol expansion, Mamluk generals seized power in Egypt and expanded into the Middle East.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the early-16th century, the Ottoman Empire rapidly conquered North Africa (save for Morocco, now under Saadi rule) to counter Spanish expansionism.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the following centuries, over a million Europeans are estimated to have been captured and enslaved by Barbary corsairs.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Ottoman regencies became more independent during the 18th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the central Sahel around Lake Chad, the Kanem–Bornu Empire ruled from the 6th century, and projected power over the Hausa Kingdoms.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] To the east during 7th century, Makuria conquered Nobatia to become the dominant power in the region and resisted Muslim expansion.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] They later entered a severe decline following civil war and Arab migrations to the Sudan and had disintegrated by the 15th century, giving rise to the Funj Sultanate.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Tunjur empire's collapse in the central Sudan saw the rise of the Bagirmi, Wadai, and Darfur sultanates, which frequently raided the populations to their south for slaves.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the Horn of Africa, Aksum lost control of the Red Sea, and its isolation from Christendom caused Ethiopian society to introspect and take inspiration from the Old Testament.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Islamised Beja invaded the Ethiopian Highlands, forcing Aksum to migrate south, where, according to tradition, Aksum's expansion was met by a Jewish or traditionalist queen who destroyed the state c.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] During the 13th century, hegemony in the Horn was contested by the Christian Zagwe, the Muslims of Shewa, and the traditionalist Damot; the Solomonic dynasty overthrew the Zagwe to found the Ethiopian Empire, while Shewa was replaced by Ifat.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Soon after, Ethiopia conquered Damot and the Muslim states, entering into a 'golden age'.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 16th century Muslims united behind Adal in *jihad* to reconquer the Muslim lands and occupy Ethiopia, until, with Portuguese assistance, Ethiopia counter-attacked and its sovereignty was restored in a reduced state.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The 16th and 17th centuries also saw Oromo invasions into the Horn, weakening Ethiopia further and causing the collapse of Adal, while Ajuran on the east coast also disintegrated.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Ethiopia briefly consolidated its authority in the late-17th century, though the turn of the century saw fragmentation and gradually-increasing anarchy, which continued throughout the 18th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the Sahel region of West Africa, the Ghana Empire formed from between the 2nd and 8th centuries, while from the 7th century the Gao Empire ruled to its east.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Almoravid capture of royal Aoudaghost led to Ghana's conversion to Islam in the 11th century, and climatic changes led to Ghana's conquest by its vassal Sosso in the 13th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Sosso was quickly overthrown by the Mali Empire who conquered Gao and dominated the trans-Saharan trade.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Mossi Kingdoms were established to its south.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The 15th century saw the crumbling of the Mali Empire, with the dominant power in the region becoming the Songhai Empire centered on Gao.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Weakened by internal conflict, in 1591 Gao was conquered by Morocco, and the political vacuum came to be filled by the Segou Empire and several other states.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The once lucrative trans-Saharan trade gradually lost its prominence to the coastal Atlantic trade with Europeans, and the following centuries saw many droughts, famines, and epidemics.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the forest regions of West Africa, various kingdoms and empires flourished, such as the Yoruba empires of Ife and Oyo, the Igbo Kingdom of Nri, the Edo Kingdom of Benin (famous for its art), the Dagomba Kingdom of Dagbon, and the Akan kingdoms of Bonoman and Adanse.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] They came into contact with the Portuguese in the 15th century which saw the start of the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Asante Empire was established in present-day Ghana.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Between 1515 and 1800, 8 million Africans were exported in the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the western Congo Basin by the 13th century there were three main confederations of states: the Seven Kingdoms, Mpemba, and one led by Vungu.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 14th century the Kingdom of Kongo emerged and dominated the region, with the Tio Kingdom to its north and Mwene Muji to its northeast.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Over the course of the late-16th and 17th centuries, the Portuguese sought to conquer Ndongo (allied to Matamba) in the Angolan Wars; despite fierce resistance from Queen Nzinga, and brief occupation of Luanda by the Dutch (allied to Kongo), Portugal controlled most of Ndongo by the 1670s.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The late-17th century saw Kongo fragment between royal houses as several vassals broke away; by the time of Kongo's restoration in 1709, it had ceased being the dominant regional power.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Also during the 17th century, in the textile-producing northeast, the Boma, Yaka, and possibly the Kuba and Pende kingdoms broke away from Mwene Muji.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the eastern Congo Basin, farmers, fishermen, and hunters (often Pygmies) built symbiotic relations.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Jan Vansina wrote that in the southern savanna 'lords of the land' held priestly roles due to their special relationship with the spirits of the land, and held sway over multiple villages, effectively ruling embryonic kingdoms.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Accordingly, as lineages grew, authority was opportunistically absorbed or incorporated by force.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The centre of the Luba Empire is yet to undergo archaeological research, meaning knowledge about its rise is limited; its foundation is typically dated to the 14th/15th centuries, though scholarly estimates range from the 8th to 17th centuries.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] A Lunda state formed in the Nkalany Valley (estimates range from c.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] 1700), in the 18th century, Lunda rapidly expanded into an extensive commonwealth across the southern savanna, using the institutions of perpetual kinship and positional succession to incorporate peoples.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Meanwhile, Luba expanded its number of tributaries, in some cases using its widely acknowledged prestige to intervene in succession disputes and distribute ritually-powerful royal regalia related to *bulopwe* (sacred kingship), in other cases using conquest.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the northern Great Lakes, the Empire of Kitara rose around the 11th century, famed for its oral traditions.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Peter Robertshaw considered its rulers (the Chwezi) to have been religious leaders who utilised networks of hill-top shrines to project authority.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Around 1500, severe droughts and famine destabilised the region, occurring again during the early-17th and 18th centuries.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Luo-speaking peoples migrated from the Upper Nile basin into modern-day Uganda, and a Biito dynasty replaced the Chwezi in Bunyoro-Kitara.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Over the following centuries, the kingdoms of Bunyoro-Kitara, Buganda, and Rwanda struggled for hegemony among others.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, Bunyoro raided states to the south such as Nkore and Rwanda.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Mpororo rose and fragmented during the 18th century, while Buganda rapidly expanded at the expense of Bunyoro to become the major power in the region.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The East African interior was inhabited by pastoralist Cushitic and Nilotic speakers, along with Bantu speakers who continued to expand and adapt to their lands while absorbing the former two; the 17th century saw the establishment of tributary systems that stabilised the region.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] On the Swahili coast the Swahili city-states thrived off of the Indian Ocean trade and gradually Islamized, giving rise to the Kilwa Sultanate from the 10th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 15th century, trade routes for Zimbabwean gold shifted north, weakening Kilwa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Portuguese arrived at the coast soon after, and exploited divisions between coastal city-states to gain control over them while utilising a powerful navy.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the 17th and 18th centuries, Lamu-Swahili cities rebelled against the Portuguese and allied the Omani Empire which supplanted Portuguese rule.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Madagascar was settled by Austronesian peoples between the 5th and 7th centuries, as societies organized at the behest of *hasina* and competed over with one another over the island's estuaries and bridgeheads.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] From around the 15th century, southern Madagascar became integrated into global trade; the Sakalava Empire rose to dominate west-coastal trade, accompanied by numerous other states, and the island saw several failed European colonial ventures.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In Southern Africa, an early kingdom was Mapungubwe, which collapsed c.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] 1300 as Great Zimbabwe, with its monumental dry-stone walls, rose to become the region's main political and economic centre.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Following shifting trade routes north to the Zambezi and unclear circumstances, Great Zimbabwe entered into decline and was succeeded by the Mutapa Empire and Kingdom of Butua in the 15th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Mutapa was briefly vassalised by the Portuguese in the 17th century, the latter-half of which saw widespread famine and disease, until Changamire Dombo revolted in the 1680s, conquered Butua to found the Rozvi Empire, and expelled all Portuguese from the Zimbabwean Plateau.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] North of the Zambezi, Maravi around Lake Malawi expanded in the 17th century, but the collapse of its succession system in the 18th century precipitated its disintegration.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] By the late-1st millennium CE, Bantu-speaking farmers populated most of Southern Africa's cultivable savannas, reaching southwards to the Kei River; they traded goods such as livestock, grain, and metal tools between communities and with hunter-gatherers.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Further south, the Dutch began colonizing the western Cape in the 17th century, and Britain seized control of the colony around the turn of the 19th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the late-18th century, the interplay of pre-existing trends of political centralization with the effects of international trade, environmental instability, and European colonisation set the *Mfecane* ("Crushing") in motion, as various African states were founded.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] By the turn of the 19th century, many of Africa's economic and political structures were unstable and brittle as a result of long-term effects of the slave trade.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In Egypt Muhammad Ali led a national movement to seize power from Ottoman suzerainty, instituting sweeping reforms and greatly strengthening Egyptian power by militaristic expansion.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Meanwhile, in West Africa the Fula *jihad*s, which had been gaining momentum throughout the 18th century, culminated in the establishment of the expansive Sokoto and Hamdullahi caliphates.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In the Horn, Ethiopia underwent reforms, seeking to revive the imperial state, something that was later achieved by Menelik II's conquests.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In Southern Africa the *Mfecane* propelled large long-distance migrations that caused widespread disruption across the vast region, while several Boer republics were founded.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] European campaigns to abolish the Atlantic slave trade led to supply refocusing on internal markets and saw the rapid growth of the Indian Ocean slave trade.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Across the continent many rulers attempted reforms and indigenous forms of 'modernisation', however these efforts were consistently undermined by European traders and missionaries as the tide of European encroachment rose.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] For 400 years, European nations had mainly limited their involvement to trading stations on the African coast, with few daring to venture inland.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Industrial Revolution in Europe produced several technological innovations which assisted them in overcoming this 400-year pattern.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] One was the development of repeating rifles, which were easier and quicker to load than muskets.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Maxim developed the maxim gun, the model of the modern-day machine gun.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] European states kept these weapons largely among themselves by refusing to sell these weapons to African leaders.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] African germs took numerous European lives and deterred permanent settlements.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Diseases such as yellow fever, sleeping sickness, yaws, and leprosy made Africa a very inhospitable place for Europeans.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The deadliest disease was malaria, endemic throughout Tropical Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In 1854, the discovery of quinine and other medical innovations helped to make conquest and colonisation in Africa possible.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] There were strong motives for the conquest of Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Raw materials were needed for European factories, and free trade was championed to prevent Africans from regulating their economies.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Prestige and imperial rivalries were at play.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Acquiring African colonies would show rivals that a nation was powerful and significant.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] These contextual factors forged the Scramble for Africa; during the late-19th and early-20th centuries the European powers partitioned and conquered almost all of Africa despite fierce resistance (only Ethiopia and Liberia remained independent).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Traditional leaders were incorporated into the colonial regimes as a form of indirect rule to extract human and natural resources and curb organized resistance.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Colonial borders were drawn unilaterally by the Europeans, often cutting across bonds of kinship, language, culture, and established routes, and sometimes incorporating groups who previously had little in common.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The threat to trade routes was mitigated by poor policing and African entrepreneurs (viewed as smugglers) who exploited the differing tax and legal schemes.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The first few decades of European colonialism saw intense violence, disorder, and atrocities, such as that of the Congo Free State, German South West Africa, and French Algeria, with the late colonial period relatively peaceful in comparison.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Colonial rule had wide-reaching effects on African societies, such as the spread of Christianity as part of the 'civilising mission'.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] African culture was strongly denigrated and persecuted, as pervasive racial discrimination deepened the scars of humiliation.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Imperial rule by Europeans continued until after the conclusion of World War II, when almost all remaining colonial territories gradually obtained formal independence.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Independence movements in Africa gained momentum following World War II, which left the major European powers weakened.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In 1951, Libya, a former Italian colony, gained independence.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In 1956, Tunisia and Morocco won their independence from France.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Ghana followed suit the next year (March 1957), becoming the first of the sub-Saharan colonies to be granted independence.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Over the next decade, waves of decolonisation took place across the continent, culminating in the 1960 Year of Africa and the establishment of the Organisation of African Unity in 1963.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Portugal's overseas presence in sub-Saharan Africa (most notably in Angola, Cape Verde, Mozambique, Guinea-Bissau, and São Tomé and Príncipe) lasted from the 16th century to 1975, after the Estado Novo regime was overthrown in a military coup in Lisbon.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Rhodesia unilaterally declared independence from the United Kingdom in 1965, under the white minority government of Ian Smith, but was not internationally recognised as an independent state (as Zimbabwe) until 1980, when black nationalists gained power after a bitter guerrilla war.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Although South Africa was one of the first African countries to gain independence, the state remained under the control of the country's white minority, initially through qualified voting rights and from 1956 by a system of racial segregation known as apartheid, until 1994.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] As of 2025, Africa contains 54 sovereign countries.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Since independence, African states have frequently been hampered by instability, corruption, violence, and authoritarianism.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The vast majority of African states are republics that operate under some form of the presidential system of rule.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] However, few of them have been able to sustain democratic governments on a permanent basis—per the criteria laid out by Lührmann et al.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] (2018), only Botswana and Mauritius have been consistently democratic for the entirety of their post-colonial history.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Most African countries have experienced several coups or periods of military dictatorship.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Between 1990 and 2018, though, the continent as a whole has trended towards more democratic governance.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Upon independence an overwhelming majority of Africans lived in extreme poverty.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The continent suffered from the lack of infrastructural or industrial development under colonial rule, along with political instability.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] With limited financial resources or access to global markets, relatively stable countries such as Kenya still experienced only very slow economic development.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Only a handful of African countries succeeded in obtaining rapid economic growth prior to 1990.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Exceptions include Libya and Equatorial Guinea, both of which possess large oil reserves.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Instability throughout the continent after decolonisation resulted primarily from marginalisation of ethnic groups, and corruption.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Faced with increasingly frequent and severe violence, military rule was widely accepted by the population of many countries as means to maintain order, and during the 1970s and 1980s a majority of African countries were controlled by military dictatorships.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Territorial disputes between nations and rebellions by groups seeking independence were also common in independent African states.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The most devastating of these was the Nigerian Civil War, fought between government forces and an Igbo separatist republic, which resulted in a famine that killed 1–2 million people.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Two civil wars in Sudan, the first lasting from 1955 to 1972 and the second from 1983 to 2005, collectively killed around 3 million.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Both were fought primarily on ethnic and religious lines.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Cold War conflicts between the United States and the Soviet Union also contributed to instability.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Both the Soviet Union and the United States offered considerable incentives to African political and military leaders who aligned themselves with the superpowers' foreign policy.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] As an example, during the Angolan Civil War, the Soviet and Cuban aligned MPLA and the American aligned UNITA received the vast majority of their military and political support from these countries.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Many African countries became highly dependent on foreign aid.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The sudden loss of both Soviet and American aid at the end of the Cold War and fall of the USSR resulted in severe economic and political turmoil in the countries most dependent on foreign support.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] There was a major famine in Ethiopia between 1983 and 1985, killing up to 1.2 million people, which most historians attribute primarily to the forced relocation of farmworkers and seizure of grain by the communist Derg government, further exacerbated by the civil war.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] In 1994 a genocide in Rwanda resulted in up to 800,000 deaths, added to a severe refugee crisis and fuelled the rise of militia groups in neighbouring countries.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] This contributed to the outbreak of the first and second Congo Wars, which were the most devastating military conflicts in modern Africa, with up to 5.5 million deaths, making it by far the deadliest conflict in modern African history and one of the costliest wars in human history.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Various conflicts between various insurgent groups and governments continue.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Since 2003, there has been an ongoing conflict in Darfur (Sudan), which peaked in intensity from 2003 to 2005 with notable spikes in violence in 2007 and 2013–15, killing around 300,000 people total.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Boko Haram Insurgency primarily within Nigeria (with considerable fighting in Niger, Chad, and Cameroon as well) has killed around 350,000 people since 2009.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Most African conflicts have been reduced to low-intensity conflicts as of 2022.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] However, the Tigray War from 2020 to 2022 killed an estimated 300,000–500,000 people, primarily due to famine.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Overall though, violence across Africa has greatly declined in the 21st century, with the end of civil wars in Angola, Sierra Leone, and Algeria in 2002, Liberia in 2003, and Sudan and Burundi in 2005.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] The Second Congo War, which involved 9 countries and several insurgent groups, ended in 2003.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] This decline in violence coincided with many countries abandoning communist-style command economies and opening up for market reforms, which over the course of the 1990s and 2000s promoted the establishment of permanent, peaceful trade between neighbouring countries (see Capitalist peace).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Improved stability and economic reforms have led to a great increase in foreign investment into many African nations, mainly from China, which further spurred economic growth.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] Between 2000 and 2014, annual GDP growth in sub-Saharan Africa averaged 5.02%, doubling its total GDP from $811 billion to $1.63 trillion (constant 2015 USD).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] North Africa experienced comparable growth rates.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] A significant part of this growth can also be attributed to the facilitated diffusion of information technologies and specifically the mobile telephone.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p01] While several individual countries have maintained high growth rates, since 2014 overall growth has considerably slowed, primarily as a result of falling commodity prices, continued lack of industrialisation, and epidemics such as Ebola and COVID-19.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Africa is the largest of the three great southward projections from the largest landmass of the Earth.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Separated from Europe by the Mediterranean Sea, it is joined to Asia at its northeast extremity by the Isthmus of Suez (transected by the Suez Canal), 163 km (101 mi) wide.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Geopolitically, Egypt's Sinai Peninsula east of the Suez Canal is often considered part of Africa as well.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The coastline is 26,000 km (16,000 mi) long, and the absence of deep indentations of the shore is illustrated by the fact that Europe, which covers only 10,400,000 km2 (4,000,000 sq mi) – about a third of the surface of Africa – has a coastline of 32,000 km (20,000 mi).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] From the most northerly point, Ras ben Sakka in Tunisia (37°21' N), to the most southerly point, Cape Agulhas in South Africa (34°51'15" S), is a distance of approximately 8,000 km (5,000 mi).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Cape Verde, 17°33'22" W, the westernmost point, is a distance of approximately 7,400 km (4,600 mi) to Ras Hafun, 51°27'52" E, the most easterly projection that neighbours Cape Guardafui, the tip of the Horn of Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Africa's largest country is Algeria, and its smallest country is Seychelles, an archipelago off the east coast.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The smallest nation on the continental mainland is The Gambia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The African plate, also known as the Nubian plate, is a major tectonic plate that includes most of the continent of Africa (except for its easternmost part) and the adjacent oceanic crust to the west and south.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] It also includes a narrow strip of Western Asia along the Mediterranean Sea, including much of Israel, Palestine and Lebanon.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] It is bounded by the North American plate and South American plate to the west (separated by the Mid-Atlantic Ridge); the Arabian plate and Somali plate to the east; the Eurasian plate, Aegean Sea plate and Anatolian plate to the north; and the Antarctic plate to the south.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Between 60 million years ago and 10 million years ago, the Somali plate began rifting from the African plate along the East African Rift.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Since the continent of Africa consists of crust from both the African and the Somali plates, some literature refers to the African plate as the *Nubian plate* to distinguish it from the continent as a whole.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The climate of Africa ranges from tropical to subarctic on its highest peaks.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Its northern half is primarily desert, or arid, while its central and southern areas contain both savanna plains and dense jungle (rainforest) regions.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In between, there is a convergence, where vegetation patterns such as sahel and steppe dominate.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Africa is the hottest continent on Earth and 60% of the entire land surface consists of drylands and deserts.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The record for the highest-ever recorded temperature, in Libya in 1922 (58 °C (136 °F)), was discredited in 2013.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Climate change in Africa is a serious threat because the continent is one of the most vulnerable regions to the effects of climate change, despite being responsible for less than 4% of global greenhouse emissions.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Climate change is causing increasingly erratic rainfall patterns, more frequent extreme weather events such as droughts, floods, and rising sea-surface temperatures across the continent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] These changes threaten food and water security, biodiversity, public health, and economic development.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Africa is currently warming faster than the rest of the world on average.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Climate change intensifies existing socioeconomic vulnerabilities.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Large segments of the African population depend on climate-sensitive livelihoods such as agriculture (55 - 62% of the workforce in sub-Saharan Africa) and already live in poverty, heightening their exposure to shocks.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Health outcomes worsen as heat stress, vector-borne diseases (such as malaria and dengue), and malnutrition become more prevalent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Over half (56%) of the over 2,000 recorded public health incidents in Africa between 2001 and 2021 were connected to climate change.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Resource scarcity contributes to displacement and conflict, particularly in fragile regions.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Urban areas, often characterized by informal settlements, face heightened risks from flooding and extreme heat.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Africa has over 3,000 protected areas, with 198 marine protected areas, 50 biosphere reserves, and 80 wetlands reserves.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Significant habitat destruction, increases in human population and poaching are reducing Africa's biological diversity and arable land.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Human encroachment, civil unrest and the introduction of non-native species threaten biodiversity in Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] This has been exacerbated by administrative problems, inadequate personnel and funding problems.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Deforestation is affecting Africa at twice the world rate, according to the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The deforestation rate of 4.08 million hectares in 2000–2015 declined to 3.45 million ha per year in 2015–2025.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Some sources claim that approximately 90% of the original, virgin forests in West Africa have been destroyed.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Over 90% of Madagascar's original forests have been destroyed since the arrival of humans 2000 years ago.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] About 65% of Africa's agricultural land suffers from soil degradation.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] It is also home to a variety of "jungle" animals including snakes and primates and aquatic life such as crocodiles and amphibians.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In addition, Africa has the largest number of megafauna species, as it was least affected by the extinction of the Pleistocene megafauna.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] African environmental problems are problems caused by the direct and indirect human impacts on the natural environment and affect humans and nearly all forms of life in Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Issues include deforestation, soil degradation, air pollution, water pollution, coastal erosion, garbage pollution, climate change, Oil spills, Biodiversity loss, and water scarcity (resulting in problems with access to safe water supply and sanitation).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] These issues result in environmental conflict and are connected to broader social struggles for democracy and sovereignty.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The scarcity of climate adaptation techniques in Africa makes it the least resilient continent to climate change.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The African Union (AU) is a continental union consisting of 55 member states.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The union was formed, with Addis Ababa, Ethiopia, as its headquarters, on 26 June 2001.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The union was officially established on 9 July 2002 as a successor to the Organisation of African Unity (OAU).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In July 2004, the African Union's Pan-African Parliament (PAP) was relocated to Midrand, in South Africa, but the African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights remained in Addis Ababa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The African Union, not to be confused with the AU Commission, is formed by the Constitutive Act of the African Union, which aims to transform the African Economic Community, a federated commonwealth, into a state under established international conventions.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The African Union has a parliamentary government, known as the African Union Government, consisting of legislative, judicial and executive organs.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] It is led by the African Union President and Head of State, who is also the President of the Pan-African Parliament.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] A person becomes AU President by being elected to the PAP, and subsequently gaining majority support in the PAP.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The government of the AU consists of all-union, regional, state, and municipal authorities, as well as hundreds of institutions, that together manage the day-to-day affairs of the institution.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Extensive human rights abuses still occur in several parts of Africa, often under the oversight of the state.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Most of such violations occur for political reasons, often as a side effect of civil war.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Countries where major human rights violations have been reported in recent times include the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Sierra Leone, Liberia, Sudan, Zimbabwe, and Ivory Coast.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] African nations have made great efforts to respect international borders as inviolate for a long time.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] For example, the Organization of African Unity (OAU), which was established in 1963 and replaced by the African Union in 2002, set the respect for the territorial integrity of each country as one of its principles in OAU Charter.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Indeed, compared with the formation of European countries, there have been fewer international conflicts in Africa for changing the borders, which has influenced country formation there and has enabled some countries to survive that might have been defeated and absorbed by others.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Yet international conflicts have played out by support for proxy armies or rebel movements.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Many states have experienced civil wars: including Rwanda, Sudan, Angola, Sierra Leone, Congo, Liberia, Ethiopia and Somalia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Wars of national liberation also often took up a Marxist, Marxist–Leninist, or Maoist character in ideological terms, where the independence of African nations was raised in Marxian terms.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Early examples included the Union of the Peoples of Cameroon armed movement against French colonialism, a Marxist–Leninist insurgency, followed by similar movements in Congo (the Simba Rebellion).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Che Guevara participated in the latter, and opined in 1967 that Africa was not ready for revolution.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Despite this, in Zanzibar before and after unification with Tanzania, forms of socialism took hold.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Even after 1990, there are some examples of Military Marxism, such as a militia established by Ernest Wamba-dia-Wamba in Eastern Congo in the 1990s.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The countries in this table are categorised according to the scheme for geographic subregions used by the United Nations, and data included are per sources in cross-referenced articles.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Where they differ, provisos are clearly indicated.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] This list contains nine territories that are administered as incorporated areas of a primarily non-African country but that belong geographically to the African continent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The continent's total nominal GDP remains behind that of several individual countries, including the United States, China, Japan, Germany, the United Kingdom, India and France.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] According to the United Nations' Human Development Report in 2003, the bottom 24 ranked nations (151st to 175th) were all African.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Poverty, illiteracy, malnutrition, inadequate water supply and sanitation, and poor health affect a large proportion of the people who reside on the African continent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In August 2008, the World Bank announced revised global poverty estimates based on a new international poverty line of $1.25 per day (versus the previous measure of $1.00).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Eighty-one percent of the sub-Saharan African population was living on less than $2.50 (PPP) per day in 2005, compared with 86% for India.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa is the least successful region of the world in reducing poverty ($1.25 per day); some 50% of the population living in poverty in 1981 (200 million people), a figure that rose to 58% in 1996 before dropping to 50% in 2005 (380 million people).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The average poor person in sub-Saharan Africa is estimated to live on only 70 cents per day, and was poorer in 2003 than in 1973, indicating increasing poverty in some areas.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Some of it is attributed to unsuccessful economic liberalisation programmes spearheaded by foreign companies and governments, but other studies have cited bad domestic government policies more than external factors.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Africa is now at risk of being in debt once again, particularly in sub-Saharan African countries.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The last debt crisis in 2005 was resolved with help from the heavily indebted poor countries scheme (HIPC).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The HIPC resulted in some positive and negative effects on the economy in Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] About ten years after the 2005 debt crisis in sub-Saharan Africa was resolved, Zambia fell back into debt.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] A small reason was due to the fall in copper prices in 2011, but the bigger reason was that a large amount of the money Zambia borrowed was wasted or pocketed by the elite.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] From 1995 to 2005, Africa's rate of economic growth increased, averaging 5% in 2005.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Some countries experienced still higher growth rates, notably Angola, Sudan and Equatorial Guinea, all of which had recently begun extracting their petroleum reserves or had expanded their oil extraction capacity.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The following table shows the projected nominal GDP and GDP per capita (at purchasing power parity) in 2026 by the IMF.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The continent is believed to hold 90% of the world's cobalt, 90% of its platinum, 50% of its gold, 98% of its chromium, 70% of its tantalite, 64% of its manganese and one-third of its uranium.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has 70% of the world's coltan, a mineral used in the production of tantalum capacitors for electronic devices such as cell phones.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The DRC also has more than 30% of the world's diamond reserves.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Guinea is the world's largest exporter of bauxite.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] As the growth in Africa has been driven mainly by services and not manufacturing or agriculture, it has been growth without jobs and without reduction in poverty levels.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In fact, the food security crisis of 2008, which took place following the global financial crisis, pushed 100 million people into food insecurity.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In 2024 nearly 307 million people in Africa were undernourished (46% of the global total), an increase of 10 million people since 2023 and 34 million from 2022.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In recent years, China has built increasingly stronger ties with African nations and is Africa's largest trading partner.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In 2007, Chinese companies invested a total of US$1 billion in Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] A Harvard University study led by professor Calestous Juma showed that Africa could feed itself by making the transition from importer to self-sufficiency.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] "African agriculture is at the crossroads; we have come to the end of a century of policies that favoured Africa's export of raw materials and importation of food.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Cooking with biogas in Tanzania; Geothermal energy infrastructure in Kenya; Coal power station in South Africa; Solar-powered lamp-light in Zambia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Energy in Africa is characterised by low per-capita consumption and limited access to modern energy services, reflecting both infrastructural and socio-economic challenges across the continent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] As of 2023, Africa accounted for just 5.5% of global total final energy consumption, with per-capita energy use more than three times lower than the global average.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The energy mix is dominated by biofuels and waste, which make up 43% of total final consumption, primarily for household cooking and heating, followed by oil products at 33%, electricity at 11%, natural gas at 9%, and coal at 4%.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Electricity access remains a major challenge, particularly in Sub-Saharan Africa, where nearly 450 million rural residents lack reliable electricity, and grid coverage is often inconsistent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Clean cooking solutions are similarly underdeveloped, leaving over 900 million people reliant on polluting fuels such as firewood, charcoal, and agricultural residues, which disproportionately affect women and children.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Transport energy is dominated by oil products, reflecting low motorisation rates and limited adoption of electric mobility, although countries such as Ethiopia, Morocco, and Egypt have begun adopting policies to reduce fossil fuel dependency.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Africa possesses some of the world's most abundant energy resources, including oil, natural gas, coal, hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and biomass, much of which remains underutilised.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] While fossil fuels such as coal, oil, and natural gas continue to dominate energy production and electricity generation in Africa, renewable sources are increasingly expanding across the continent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Hydropower, solar, wind, geothermal, and modern biomass are growing in capacity, though their deployment remains uneven and limited compared to the continent's vast potential.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Hydropower is the largest non-combustible renewable source, while solar energy offers immense potential due to high irradiation levels, particularly in the Sahara and Sahel.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] There are regional differences: North Africa is dominated by oil and gas production, Southern Africa by coal and hydropower, East Africa by hydropower and geothermal, and West and Central Africa face major electrification gaps despite hydroelectric potential.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Water development and management are complex in Africa due to the multiplicity of trans-boundary water resources (rivers, lakes and aquifers).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Around 75% of sub-Saharan Africa falls within 53 international river basin catchments that traverse multiple borders.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] This particular constraint can also be converted into an opportunity if the potential for trans-boundary cooperation is harnessed in the development of the area's water resources.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] A multi-sectoral analysis of the Zambezi River, for example, shows that riparian cooperation could lead to a 23% increase in firm energy production without any additional investments.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] A number of institutional and legal frameworks for transboundary cooperation exist, such as the Zambezi River Authority, the Southern African Development Community (SADC) Protocol, Volta River Authority and the Nile Basin Commission.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] However, additional efforts are required to further develop political will, as well as the financial capacities and institutional frameworks needed for win-win multilateral cooperative actions and optimal solutions for all riparians.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Africa is considered by anthropologists to be the most genetically diverse continent as a result of being the longest inhabited.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Africa's population has rapidly increased over the last 40 years, and is consequently relatively young.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In some African states, more than half the population is under 25 years of age.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The total number of people in Africa increased from 229 million in 1950 to 630 million in 1990.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] As of 2021, the population of Africa is estimated at 1,394 million.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Africa's total population surpassing other continents is fairly recent; African population surpassed Europe in the 1990s, while the Americas was overtaken sometime around the year 2000.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] This increase in number of babies born in Africa compared to the rest of the world is expected to reach approximately 37% in the year 2050; while in 1990 sub-Saharan Africa accounted for only 16% of the world's births.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The total fertility rate (children per woman) for Sub-Saharan Africa is 4.7 as of 2018, the highest in the world.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] All countries in sub-Saharan Africa had TFRs (average number of children) above replacement level in 2019 and accounted for 27.1% of global livebirths.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In 2021, sub-Saharan Africa accounted for 29% of global births.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Speakers of Bantu languages (part of the Niger–Congo family) are the majority in southern, central and southeast Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The Bantu-speaking peoples from the Sahel progressively expanded over most of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] But there are also several Nilotic groups in South Sudan and East Africa, the mixed Swahili people on the Swahili Coast, and a few remaining indigenous Khoisan ("San" or "Bushmen") and Pygmy peoples in Southern and Central Africa, respectively.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Bantu-speaking Africans also predominate in Gabon and Equatorial Guinea, and are found in parts of southern Cameroon.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In the Kalahari Desert of Southern Africa, the distinct people known as the Bushmen (also "San", closely related to, but distinct from "Hottentots") have long been present.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The San are physically distinct from other Africans and are the indigenous people of southern Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Pygmies are the pre-Bantu indigenous peoples of central Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The peoples of West Africa primarily speak Niger–Congo languages, belonging mostly to its non-Bantu branches, though some Nilo-Saharan and Afro-Asiatic speaking groups are also found.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The Niger–Congo-speaking Yoruba, Igbo, Fulani, Akan, and Wolof ethnic groups are the largest and most influential.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In the central Sahara, Mandinka or Mande groups are most significant.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Chadic-speaking groups, including the Hausa, are found in more northerly parts of the region nearest to the Sahara, and Nilo-Saharan communities, such as the Songhai, Kanuri, and Zarma, are found in the eastern parts of West Africa bordering Central Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The peoples of North Africa consist of three main indigenous groups: Berbers in the northwest, Egyptians in the northeast, and Nilo-Saharan-speaking peoples in the east.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The Arabs who arrived in the 7th century AD introduced the Arabic language and Islam to North Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The Semitic Phoenicians (who founded Carthage) and Hyksos, the Indo-Iranian Alans, the Indo-European Greeks, Romans, and Vandals settled in North Africa as well.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Significant Berber communities remain within Morocco and Algeria in the 21st century, while, to a lesser extent, Berber speakers are also present in some regions of Tunisia and Libya.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The Berber-speaking Tuareg and other often-nomadic peoples are the principal inhabitants of the Saharan interior of North Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In Mauritania, there is a small but near-extinct Berber community in the north and Niger–Congo-speaking peoples in the south, though in both regions Arabic and Arab culture predominates.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In Sudan, although Arabic and Arab culture predominate, it is mostly inhabited by groups that originally spoke Nilo-Saharan, such as the Nubians, Fur, Masalit and Zaghawa, who, over the centuries, have variously intermixed with migrants from the Arabian peninsula.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Small communities of Afro-Asiatic-speaking Beja nomads can also be found in Egypt and Sudan.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In the Horn of Africa, some Ethiopian and Eritrean groups (like the Amhara and Tigrayans, collectively known as Habesha) speak languages from the Semitic branch of the Afro-Asiatic language family, while the Oromo and Somali speak languages from the Cushitic branch of Afro-Asiatic.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Prior to the decolonisation movements of the post-World War II era, Europeans were represented in every part of Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Decolonization during the 1960s and 1970s often resulted in the mass emigration of white settlers—especially from Algeria and Morocco (1.6 million *pieds-noirs* in North Africa), Kenya, Congo, Rhodesia, Mozambique and Angola.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Between 1975 and 1977, over a million colonials returned to Portugal alone.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Nevertheless, white Africans remain an important minority in many African states, particularly Zimbabwe, Namibia, Réunion, and South Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The country with the largest white African population is South Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Dutch and British diasporas represent the largest communities of European ancestry on the continent today.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] European colonisation also brought sizable groups of Asians, particularly from the Indian subcontinent, to British colonies.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Large Indian communities are found in South Africa, and smaller ones are present in Kenya, Tanzania, and some other southern and southeast African countries.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The large Indian community in Uganda was expelled by the dictator Idi Amin in 1972, though many have since returned.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The islands in the Indian Ocean are also populated primarily by people of Asian origin, often mixed with Africans and Europeans.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The Malagasy people of Madagascar are an Austronesian people, but those along the coast are generally mixed with Bantu, Arab, Indian and European origins.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Malay and Indian ancestries are also important components in the group of people known in South Africa as Cape Coloureds (people with origins in two or more races and continents).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] During the 20th century, small but economically important communities of Lebanese have also developed in the larger coastal cities of West and East Africa, respectively.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The Sahara served as a trans-regional passageway and place of dwelling for people in Africa during various humid phases and periods throughout the history of Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] As early as 11,000 years ago, Sub-Saharan West Africans, bearing macrohaplogroup L (e.g., L1b1a11, L1b1a6a, L1b1a8, L1b1a9a1, L2a1k, L3d1b1a), may have migrated through North Africa and into Europe, mostly into southern Europe (e.g., Iberia).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The genetic marker E1b1 was identified to have wide distribution across Egypt, with "P2/215/M35.1 (E1b1b), for short M35, likely also originated in eastern tropical Africa, and is predominantly distributed in an arc from the Horn of Africa up through Egypt".
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The R haplogroup has also been identified to have high frequencies in central Saharan Africa, among some Afro-Asiatic and Nilo-Saharan language speaking groups.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Genetic evidence has identified the Horn of Africa to be the source of a genetic marker "M35/215" Y-chromosome lineage for a significant population component which moved north from that region into Egypt and the Levant.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Historian Christopher Ehret argued that this genetic distribution paralleled the spread of the Afrasian language family with the movement of people from the Horn of Africa into Egypt and added a new demic component to the existing population of Egypt 17,000 years ago.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] According to a recent study, the Arab migrations to the Maghreb was mainly a demographic process that heavily implied gene flow and remodelled the genetic structure of the Maghreb region in North Africa, rather than a mere cultural replacement as claimed by older studies.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Another study found out that the majority of J-M267 (Eu10) chromosomes in the Maghreb are due to the recent gene flow caused by the Arab migrations to the Maghreb in the first millennium CE as both southern Qahtanite and northern Adnanite Arabs added to the heterogenous Maghrebi ethnic melting pot.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The Eu10 chromosome pool in the Maghreb is derived not only from early Neolithic dispersions from Western Asia but to a much greater extent from recent expansions of Arab tribes from the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] David Schoenbrun, Christopher Ehret, Steven A.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Brandt and Shomarka Keita (2025) have highlighted the problematic categorisation of genetic haplogroups characterised as ‘African’ and ‘Eurasian' in North African genome studies.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In reference to the van de Loosdrecht et al.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In their view, identifying a range of African populations may still remain an issue “since the idea of ‘African’ still gets stereotyped or restricted.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] (Accepting the southwestern Asian/Levantine geographical continuity with Africa eliminates a conceptual barrier related to racio-typological thinking permitting an Africasian construct analogous to Eurasian.)”.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] While Africans profess a wide variety of religious beliefs, the majority of the people respect African religions or parts of them.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] However, in formal surveys or census, most people will identify with major religions that came from outside the continent, mainly through colonisation.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] There are several reasons for this, the main one being the colonial idea that African religious beliefs and practices are not good enough.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Religious beliefs and statistics on religious affiliation are difficult to come by since they are often a sensitive topic for governments with mixed religious populations.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] According to the *World Book Encyclopedia*, Islam and Christianity are the two largest religions in Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Islam is most prevalent in Northern Africa, and is the state religion of many North African countries, such as Algeria, where 99% of the population practices Islam.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The majority of people in most governments in Southern, Southeast, and Central Africa, as well as in a sizable portion of the Horn of Africa and West Africa, identify as Christians.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] The Coptic Christians constitute a sizable minority in Egypt, and the Ethiopian Orthodox Church is the largest church in Ethiopia, with 36 million and 51 million adherents.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] According to Encyclopædia Britannica, 45% of the population are Christians, 40% are Muslims, and 10% follow traditional religions.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] A small number of Africans are Hindu, Buddhist, Confucianist, Baháʼí, or Jewish.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] There is also a minority of people in Africa who are irreligious.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] By most estimates, well over a thousand languages (UNESCO has estimated around two thousand) are spoken in Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Most are of African origin, though some are of European or Asian origin.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Africa is the most multilingual continent in the world, and it is not rare for individuals to fluently speak not only multiple African languages, but one or more European ones as well.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Following the end of colonialism, nearly all African countries adopted official languages that originated outside the continent, although several countries also granted legal recognition to indigenous languages (such as Swahili, Yoruba, Igbo and Hausa).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In numerous countries, English and French (*see African French*) are used for communication in the public sphere such as government, commerce, education and the media.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Arabic, Portuguese, Afrikaans and Spanish are examples of languages that trace their origin to outside of Africa, and that are used by millions of Africans today, both in the public and private spheres.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Italian is spoken by some in former Italian colonies in Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] German is spoken in Namibia, as it was a former German protectorate.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In total, at least a fifth of Africans speak the former colonial languages.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Moreover, in recent years some African countries have been considering removing their official former colonial languages, such as Mali, Burkina Faso and Niger which removed French as an official language in the 2020s in favour of native languages, while also renaming colonial street names.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] More than 85% of individuals in Africa use traditional medicine as an alternative to often expensive allopathic medical health care and costly pharmaceutical products.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] AIDS in post-colonial Africa is a prevalent issue.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Although the continent is home to about 15.2 percent of the world's population, more than two-thirds of the total infected worldwide—some 35 million people—were Africans, of whom 15 million have already died.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Sub-Saharan Africa alone accounted for an estimated 69 percent of all people living with HIV and 70 percent of all AIDS deaths in 2011.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] In the countries of sub-Saharan Africa most affected, AIDS has raised death rates and lowered life expectancy among adults between the ages of 20 and 49 by about twenty years.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p02] Furthermore, the life expectancy in many parts of Africa has declined, largely as a result of the HIV/AIDS epidemic with life-expectancy in some countries reaching as low as thirty-four years.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Africa is divided into a great number of ethnic cultures.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] In recent times, the call for a much greater emphasis on the cultural dimension in all aspects of development has become increasingly vocal.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Some aspects of traditional African cultures have become less practised in recent years as a result of neglect and suppression by colonial and post-colonial regimes.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] For example, African customs were discouraged, and African languages were prohibited in mission schools, while colonialists such as Leopold II of Belgium attempted to "civilize" Africans by discouraging polygamy and witchcraft.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Abiola Irele and Simon Gikandi comment that the current identity of African literature had its genesis in the "traumatic encounter between Africa and Europe".
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] On the other hand, Mhoze Chikowero believes that Africans deployed music, dance, spirituality, and other performative cultures to (re)assert themselves as active agents and indigenous intellectuals, to unmake their colonial marginalisation and reshape their own destinies.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] As of March 2023, 98 African properties are listed by UNESCO as World Heritage Sites.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Among these proprieties, 54 are cultural sites, 39 are natural sites and 5 are mixed sites.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] The List of World Heritage in Danger includes 15 African sites.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] African art refers to works of visual art, including works of sculpture, painting, metalwork, and pottery, originating from the various peoples of the African continent and influenced by distinct, indigenous traditions of aesthetic expression.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] While the various artistic traditions of such a large and diverse continent display considerable regional and cultural variety, there are consistent artistic themes, recurring motifs, and unifying elements across the broad spectrum of the African visual expression.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] As is the case for every artistic tradition in human history, African art was created within specific social, political, and religious contexts.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Likewise, African art was often created not purely for art's sake, but rather with some practical, spiritual, and/or didactic purpose in mind.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] In general, African art prioritizes conceptual and symbolic representation over realism, aiming to visualize the subject's spiritual essence.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Ethiopian art, heavily influenced by Ethiopia's long-standing Christian tradition, is also different from most African art, where Traditional African religion (with Islam prevalent in the north east and north west presently) was dominant until the 20th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] African art includes prehistoric and ancient art, the Islamic art of West Africa, the Christian art of East Africa, and the traditional artifacts of these and other regions.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Many African sculptures were historically made of wood and other natural materials that have not survived from earlier than a few centuries ago, although rare older pottery and metal figures can be found in some areas.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Some of the earliest decorative objects, such as shell beads and evidence of paint, have been discovered in Africa, dating to the Middle Stone Age.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Masks are important elements in the art of many people, along with human figures, and are often highly stylized.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] There exist diverse styles, which can often be observed within a single context of origin and may be influenced by the intended use of the object.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Nevertheless, broad regional trends are discernible.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Sculpture is most common among "groups of settled cultivators in the areas drained by the Niger and Congo rivers" in West Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Direct images of deities are relatively infrequent, but masks in particular are or were often made for ritual ceremonies.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Since the late 19th century, there has been an increasing amount of African art in Western collections, the finest pieces of which are displayed as part of the history of colonization.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] African art had an important influence on European Modernist art, which was inspired by their interest in abstract depiction.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] It was this appreciation of African sculpture that has been attributed to the very concept of "African art", as seen by European and American artists and art historians.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Obidoh Freeborn posits that colonialism is one element that has created the character of modern African art.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] According to authors Douglas Fraser and Herbert M.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Author Chika Okeke-Agulu states that "the racist infrastructure of British imperial enterprise forced upon the political and cultural guardians of empire a denial and suppression of an emergent sovereign Africa and modernist art".
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] scaling: small parts of the structure tend to look similar to larger parts, such as a circular village made of circular houses.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] African architecture in some areas has been influenced by external cultures for centuries, according to available evidence.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Western architecture has influenced coastal areas since the late 15th century and is now an important source of inspiration for many larger buildings, particularly in major cities.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] African architecture uses a wide range of materials, including thatch, stick/wood, mud, mudbrick, rammed earth, and stone.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] These material preferences vary by region: North Africa for stone and rammed earth, the Horn of Africa for stone and mortar, West Africa for mud/adobe, Central Africa for thatch/wood and more perishable materials, Southeast and Southern Africa for stone and thatch/wood.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Cinema of Africa refers to the film industries and films produced in the continent of Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] It covers both the history and present of the making or screening of films on the African continent, and also refers to the persons involved in this form of audiovisual culture.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] It dates back to the late 19th century, when film reels were the primary cinematic technology in use.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Cairo has been the capital of film industry in Africa since the early 20th century to the present day.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] As there are more than 50 countries with audiovisual traditions, there is no one single 'African cinema'.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Both historically and culturally, there are major regional differences between North African and sub-Saharan cinemas, and between the cinemas of different countries.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] The Egyptian film industry and the Tunisian are also among the oldest in the world.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Cinema of Egypt in particular is the most established and flourishing industry in Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Pioneers Auguste and Louis Lumière screened their films in Alexandria, Cairo, Tunis, Susa, Libya and Hammam-Lif, Tunisia in 1896.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Albert Samama Chikly is often cited as the first producer of indigenous African cinema, screening his own short documentaries in the casino of Tunis as early as December 1905.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] The continent of Africa and its music is vast and highly diverse, with different regions and nations maintaining distinct musical traditions.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] African music includes genres such as makwaya, highlife, mbube, township music, jùjú, fuji, jaiva, afrobeat, afrofusion, mbalax, Congolese rumba, soukous, ndombolo, makossa, kizomba, and taarab, among others.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] African music also uses a wide variety of instruments from across the continent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] The music and dance traditions of the African diaspora, shaped to varying degrees by African musical traditions, include American genres such as Dixieland jazz, blues, and jazz, as well as Caribbean styles such as calypso (see kaiso), and soca.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Latin American music genres including cumbia, salsa, son cubano, rumba, conga, bomba, samba, and zouk developed from the music of enslaved Africans and have, in turn, influenced contemporary African popular music.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] African dance (also Afro dance, Afrodance and Afro-dance) refers to the various dance styles of sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] These dances are closely connected with the traditional rhythms and music traditions of the region.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Music and dancing is an integral part of many traditional African societies.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Songs and dances facilitate teaching and promoting social values, the celebration of special events and major life milestones, the performance of oral history and other recitations, and spiritual experiences.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] African dance uses the concepts of polyrhythm and total body articulation.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] African dances are often a collective activity performed in large groups, with significant interaction between dancers and onlookers.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Fifty-four African countries have football teams in the Confederation of African Football.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Egypt has won the African Cup seven times, and a record-making three times in a row.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Cameroon, Nigeria, Morocco, Senegal, Ghana, and Algeria have advanced to the knockout stage of recent FIFA World Cups.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Morocco, at the 2022 World Cup in Qatar was the first African nation to reach the semi-finals of the FIFA Men's World Cup.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] South Africa hosted the 2010 World Cup tournament, becoming the first African country to do so.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] The top clubs in each African football league play the CAF Champions League, while lower-ranked clubs compete in CAF Confederation Cup.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] In recent years, the continent has progressed in terms of state-of-the-art basketball facilities, which have been built in cities such as Cairo, Dakar, Johannesburg, Kigali, Luanda, and Rades.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] The number of African basketball players who drafted into the U.S.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] NBA has experienced growth in the 2010s.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Cricket is popular in some African nations.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] South Africa and Zimbabwe have Test status, while Kenya is the leading non-test team and previously had One-Day International cricket (ODI) status (from 10 October 1997, until 30 January 2014).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] The three countries jointly hosted the 2003 Cricket World Cup.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Namibia is the other African country to have played in a World Cup.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Morocco, in northern Africa, hosted the 2002 Morocco Cup, but the national team has never qualified for a major tournament.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Rugby is popular in several southern African nations.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Namibia and Zimbabwe have appeared on multiple occasions at the Rugby World Cup, while South Africa is the most successful national team at the Rugby World Cup, having won the tournament on four occasions, in 1995, 2007, 2019, and 2023.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Traditional sports were strictly marginalised during the colonial era, and many are dying or have gone extinct under the pressure of modernisation, however lots remain popular despite not having formal governmental recognition or support.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/africa-p03] Some examples are Senegalese wrestling, Dambe, Nguni stick-fighting, and Savika.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/african-beach-games] The **African Beach Games** is a continental multi-sport event held among athletes from Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/african-beach-games] The Games are organised under the governance of the Association of National Olympic Committees of Africa (ANOCA).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/african-beach-games] The Games were announced by the ANOCA President, Lassana Palenfo, in May 2015.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/african-beach-games] All of the competing nations are for the African continent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/african-beach-games] In October 2021, Baseball5 was added as a full medal sport for the 2023 edition.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/association-of-national-olympic-committees-of-africa] It is currently headquartered in Abuja, Nigeria.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/association-of-national-olympic-committees-of-africa] It serves as the successor to **Standing Committee of African Sports** or **Comité permanent du sport africain** founded in 1965 in Brazzaville, Republic of Congo.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/association-of-national-olympic-committees-of-africa] It often assembles with other continental NOCs in the form of the Association of National Olympic Committees (ANOC).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/association-of-national-olympic-committees-of-africa] The Association of National Olympic Committees of Africa (ANOCA) was founded on June 28, 1981, in Lome, Togo.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/association-of-national-olympic-committees-of-africa] In July 1965, ANOCA's predecessor, the **Standing Committee of African Sports** (**SCAS**) was founded in Brazzaville as Comité Permanent du Sport Africain (CPSA).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/association-of-national-olympic-committees-of-africa] Consequently, that title for the sports continental body changed to the **Supreme Council for Sports in Africa** (**SCSA**) on 14 December 1966 in Bamako, Mali.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/association-of-national-olympic-committees-of-africa] On 4 March 2023, ANOCA announced their support for the International Olympic Committee's decision to reinstate Russian and Belarusian athletes as neutrals amidst the Russo-Ukrainian war, as well as the countries' participation in the Olympics.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/association-of-national-olympic-committees-of-africa] In the following table, the year in which the NOC was recognized by the International Olympic Committee (IOC) is also given if it is different from the year in which the NOC was created.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/beach-sports] Many are sand-based adaptations of sports already well established on other surfaces; most are played in smaller playing areas than their parent sports due to the more difficult and exhausting nature of traversing such a yielding terrain.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/beach-sports] The popularity and range of beach sports has experienced a notable rise since the emergence of pro beach volleyball as a successful commercial venture in the 1980s.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/beach-sports] Beach sports are practiced from a range of casual and non-competitive to professional-level competition.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/beach-sports] The definition of beach sports is also frequently extended to include water sports conducted in an ocean or similar waterbody, overlooked by an adjacent beach which forms an integral part of the aesthetic and culture of such sports; this list excludes these.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/beach-sports] The worldwide growth of beach sports has given birth to multiple Olympic-style multi-sport events dedicated in large part to beach sports competition (water sports are also usually included).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] The reported number of inhabitants varies from 100,000 to 400,000 and the population quadruples due to tourists' arrival in the summer.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] It is particularly known for jasmine, which is the namesake of the tourist resort of Yasmine Hammamet.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] All over Hammamet, souvenirs crafted from jasmine can be found.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Around Hammamet, suburbs are being built as migrants from the southern region of the country come to find employment.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] As a popular tourist destination, the city is economically important to Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] The 2005 World Scout Conference was held in Hammamet.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] In the 1st century, there was a settlement here known as Pupput.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] It was a town (now in the suburbs of Hammamet) that became a Roman colony in the 2nd century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] In the 13th century, walls around town were built and medina of Hammamet was built in the 15th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Then it came under Spanish and Turkish rule.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] In 1601 it was the object of a successful Spanish attack.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] At that time the Spanish name for the place was "La Mahometa".
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Alonso de Contreras participated and tells the story in his autobiography.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Three hundred men took seven hundred prisoners, mostly women, and children because most of the men in the town had fled, On 14 August 1605 there was another Spanish attack in which Contreras also participated but this time the result was disastrous for the attackers.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] In World War II, it became one of the headquarters of the Nazi general Erwin Rommel.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Festival international d'Hammamet was established in 1964.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Former Italian prime minister Bettino Craxi moved to Hammamet in 1994 as a fugitive.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Hammamet is located in Nabeul Governorate in the east of Tunisia, it located to in the coast of Hammamet Golf.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Hammamet is limited by Nabeul in northeast, Bou Argoub in North and Grombalia in northwest.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Hammamet is located near of two airports : Tunis-Carthage Airport (70 km) and Enfidha Airport (50 km).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] A fast and comfortable coach service runs from Tunis bus station.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Tourism represents a big sector of the city's economy.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Yassmine Hammamet is a seaside resort developed in the late 1990s.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] It's a touristic station modeled on Port El-Kantaoui located in the Gulf of Hammamet.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] It was Developed by the *Société d'études et de développement d'Hammamet-Sud* (SEDHS), and covers 277 hectares.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Yassmine Hammamet has 11 hotels of 5 stars, 25 hotels of 4 stars and 8 hotels of 3 stars.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] A reproduction of an Arab medina called *Medina Mediterranea*, with its ramparts, souks, traditional housing, a theme park (Carthage Land) and a conference center have been set up.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] In addition, two casinos, seven thalassotherapy centers, a 1.5-kilometer long esplanade with its shopping malls, green spaces and entertainment centers complete the resort's layout.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Hammamet has others tourist resorts like Hammamet Nord, Hammamet Sud and the Medina.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] Hammamet is served by the Hammamet International Festival; a big Festival that takes place in summer.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] The climate is very much like the climate in Sousse.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/hammamet-tunisia] It borders a Hot-summer Mediterranean climate (Csa) and a Hot semi-arid climate (BSh) due to dry ground and hot temperatures in the summer.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Beginning in early antiquity, Tunisia was inhabited by the indigenous Berbers.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Phoenicians, a Semitic people, began to arrive in the 12th century BC, settling on the coast and establishing several settlements, of which Carthage emerged as the most powerful by the 7th century BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The descendants of the Phoenician settlers came to be known as the Punic people.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Ancient Carthage was a major mercantile empire and a military rival to the Roman Republic until 146 BC when it was defeated by the Romans who occupied Tunisia for most of the next 800 years.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Romans introduced Christianity and left architectural legacies like the Amphitheatre of El Jem.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In the 7th century AD, Arab Muslims conquered Tunisia and settled with their tribes and families, bringing Islam and Arab culture.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] A later large-scale Arab migration of Banu Hilal and Banu Sulaym tribes in the 11th-12th centuries accelerated this process.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] By around the 15th century, the region of modern-day Tunisia had already been almost completely Arabized.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Then, in 1546, the Ottoman Empire established control, holding sway until 1881, when the French conquered Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In 1956, Tunisia gained independence as the Tunisian Republic.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Today, Tunisia's culture and identity are rooted in this centuries-long intersection of different cultures and ethnicities.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In 2011, the Tunisian Revolution, which was triggered by dissatisfaction with the lack of freedom and democracy under the 24-year rule of President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali, overthrew his regime and catalyzed the broader Arab Spring movement across the region.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Free multiparty parliamentary elections were held shortly thereafter; the country again voted for parliament on 26 October 2014, and for president on 23 November 2014.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] From 2014 to 2020, it was considered the only democratic state in the Arab world, according to *The Economist Democracy Index*.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] After democratic backsliding under President Kais Saied, Tunisia was rated a hybrid regime in 2022 and as of 2025 it no longer has free and fair elections according to Freedom House.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] It is one of the few countries in Africa ranking high on the Human Development Index, with one of the highest per capita incomes on the continent, ranking 129th in GDP per capita income.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia is well integrated into the international community.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] It maintains close economic and political relations with some European countries, particularly with France and Italy, due to their geographical proximity.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia also has an association agreement with the European Union and has attained the status of a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The word *Tunisia* is derived from Tunis, a central urban hub and the capital of modern-day Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The present form of the name, with its Latinate suffix *-ia*, evolved from French *Tunisie*, in turn generally associated with the Berber root ⵜⵏⵙ, transcribed *tns*, which means "to lay down" or "encampment".
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] It is sometimes also associated with the Carthage goddess Tanith (or Tunit), and the ancient city of Tynes.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The French derivative *Tunisie* was adopted in some European languages with slight modifications, introducing a distinctive name to designate the country.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Other languages have left the name untouched, such as the Russian Туни́с (*Tunís*) and Spanish *Túnez*.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In this case, the same name is used for both country and city, as with the Arabic تونس, and only by context can one tell the difference.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In English, Tunisia before independence was also often called simply "Tunis", a name that persisted until the 1940s; under French influence, the neologism "Tunisia", adapted from *Tunisie*, gradually took hold.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The adjective "Tunisian" first appeared in English in 1825; the previous adjectival form was "Tunisine".
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Farming methods reached the Nile Valley from the Fertile Crescent region about 5000 BC, and spread to the Maghreb by about 4000 BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Agricultural communities in the humid coastal plains of central Tunisia then were ancestors of today's Berber tribes.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] It was believed in ancient times that Africa was originally populated by Gaetulians and Libyans, both nomadic peoples.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] According to the Roman historian Sallust, the demigod Hercules died in Spain and his polyglot eastern army was left to settle the land, with some migrating to Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Persians went to the West and intermarried with the Gaetulians and became the Numidians.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Medes settled and were known as Mauri, later Moors.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Numidians and Moors belonged to the race from which the Berbers are descended.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The translated meaning of Numidian is Nomad and indeed the people were semi-nomadic until the reign of Masinissa of the Massyli tribe.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] At the beginning of recorded history, Tunisia was inhabited by Berber tribes.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Its coast was settled by Phoenicians starting as early as the 12th century BC (Bizerte, Utica).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The city of Carthage was founded in the 9th century BC by Phoenicians.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Legend says that Dido from Tyre, now in modern-day Lebanon, founded the city in 814 BC, as retold by the Greek writer Timaeus of Tauromenium.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The settlers of Carthage brought their culture and religion from Phoenicia, now present-day Lebanon and adjacent areas.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] After the series of wars with Greek city-states of Sicily in the 5th century BC, Carthage rose to power and eventually became the dominant civilization in the Western Mediterranean.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The people of Carthage worshipped a pantheon of Middle Eastern gods including Baal and Tanit.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tanit's symbol, a simple female figure with extended arms and long dress, is a popular icon found in ancient sites.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The founders of Carthage also established a Tophet, which was altered in Roman times.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] A Carthaginian invasion of Italy led by Hannibal during the Second Punic War, one of a series of wars with Rome, nearly crippled the rise of Roman power.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] From the conclusion of the Second Punic War in 202 BC, Carthage functioned as a client state of the Roman Republic for another 50 years.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Following the Battle of Carthage which began in 149 BC during the Third Punic War, Carthage was conquered by Rome in 146 BC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Following its conquest, the Romans renamed Carthage to Africa, incorporating it as a province.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Berber bishop Donatus Magnus was the founder of a Christian group known as the Donatists.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] During the 5th and 6th centuries (from 430 to 533 AD), the Germanic Vandals invaded and ruled over a kingdom in Northwest Africa that included present-day Tripoli.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The region was easily reconquered in 533–534 AD, during the rule of Emperor Justinian I, by the Eastern Romans led by General Belisarius, preluding a 165-year era of Byzantine rule.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Sometime between the second half of the 7th century and the early part of the 8th century, Arab Muslim conquest occurred in the region.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] They founded the first Islamic city in Northwest Africa, Kairouan.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] It was there in 670 AD that the Mosque of Uqba, or the Great Mosque of Kairouan, was constructed.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] This mosque is the oldest and most prestigious sanctuary in the Muslim West with the oldest standing minaret in the world; it is also considered a masterpiece of Islamic art and architecture.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Arab migration to the Maghreb began during this time.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The region in its entirety was taken in 695, retaken by the Byzantine Eastern Romans in 697, but lost permanently in 698.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The transition from a Latin-speaking Christian Berber society to a Muslim and mostly Arabic-speaking society took over 400 years (the equivalent process in Egypt and the Fertile Crescent took 600 years) and resulted in the final disappearance of Christianity and Latin in the 12th or 13th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The majority of the population were not Muslim until quite late in the 9th century; a vast majority were during the 10th.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Also, some Tunisian Christians emigrated; some richer members of society did so after the conquest in 698 and others were welcomed by Norman rulers to Sicily or Italy in the 11th and 12th centuries – the logical destination because of the 1200 year close connection between the two regions.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Arab governors of Tunis founded the Aghlabid dynasty, which ruled Tunisia, Tripolitania and eastern Algeria from 800 to 909.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia flourished under Arab rule when extensive systems were constructed to supply towns with water for household use and irrigation that promoted agriculture (especially olive production).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] This prosperity permitted luxurious court life and was marked by the construction of new palace cities such as al-Abbasiya (809) and Raq Adda (877).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] After conquering Cairo, the Fatimids abandoned Tunisia and parts of Eastern Algeria to the local Zirids (972–1148).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Zirid Tunisia flourished in many areas: agriculture, industry, trade, and religious and secular learning.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Management by the later Zirid emirs was neglectful though, and political instability was connected to the decline of Tunisian trade and agriculture.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The depredation of the Tunisian campaigns by the Banu Hilal, a warlike Arab tribe encouraged by the Fatimids of Egypt to seize Northwest Africa, sent the region's rural and urban economic life into further decline.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Consequently, the region underwent rapid urbanisation as famines depopulated the countryside and industry shifted from agriculture to manufactures.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Arab historian Ibn Khaldun wrote that the lands ravaged by Banu Hilal invaders had become completely arid desert.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The main Tunisian cities were conquered by the Normans of Sicily under the Kingdom of Africa in the 12th century, but following the conquest of Tunisia in 1159–1160 by the Almohads the Normans were evacuated to Sicily.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Communities of Tunisian Christians would still exist in Nefzaoua up to the 14th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Almohads initially ruled over Tunisia through a governor, usually a near relative of the Caliph.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Despite the prestige of the new masters, the country was still unruly, with continuous rioting and fighting between the townsfolk and wandering Arabs and Turks, the latter being subjects of the Muslim Armenian adventurer Karakush.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Also, Tunisia was occupied by Ayyubids between 1182 and 1183 and again between 1184 and 1187.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The greatest threat to Almohad rule in Tunisia was the Banu Ghaniya, relatives of the Almoravids, who from their base in Mallorca tried to restore Almoravid rule over the Maghreb.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Around 1200 they succeeded in extending their rule over the whole of Tunisia until they were crushed by Almohad troops in 1207.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] After this success, the Almohads installed Walid Abu Hafs as the governor of Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia remained part of the Almohad state, until 1230 when the son of Abu Hafs declared himself independent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] During the reign of the Hafsid dynasty from their capital Tunis, fruitful commercial relationships were established with several Christian Mediterranean states.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In the late 16th century the coast became a pirate stronghold.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In the last years of the Hafsid dynasty, Spain seized many of the coastal cities, but these were recovered by the Ottoman Empire.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The first Ottoman conquest of Tunis took place in 1534 under the command of Barbarossa Hayreddin Pasha, the younger brother of Oruç Reis, who was the Kapudan Pasha of the Ottoman Fleet during the reign of Suleiman the Magnificent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] However, it was not until the final Ottoman reconquest of Tunis from Spain in 1574 under Kapudan Pasha Uluç Ali Reis that the Ottomans permanently acquired the former Hafsid Tunisia, retaining it until the French conquest of Tunisia in 1881.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Initially under Turkish rule from Algiers, soon the Ottoman Porte appointed directly for Tunis a governor called the Pasha supported by janissary forces.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Before long, however, Tunisia became in effect an autonomous province, under the local bey.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Under its Turkish governors, the beys, Tunisia attained virtual independence.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Hussein dynasty of beys, established in 1705, lasted until 1957.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] This evolution of status was from time to time challenged without success by Algiers.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] During this era, the governing councils controlling Tunisia remained largely composed of a foreign elite who continued to conduct state business in the Turkish language.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Attacks on European shipping were made by corsairs, primarily from Algiers, but also from Tunis and Tripoli, yet after a long period of declining raids the growing power of the European states finally forced its termination.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In the 19th century, the rulers of Tunisia became aware of the ongoing efforts at political and social reform in the Ottoman capital.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Bey of Tunis then, by his own lights but informed by the Turkish example, attempted to effect a modernizing reform of institutions and the economy.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisian international debt grew unmanageable.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] This was the reason or pretext for French forces to establish a protectorate in 1881.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In 1869, Tunisia declared itself bankrupt and an international financial commission took control over its economy.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In 1881, using the pretext of a Tunisian incursion into Algeria, the French invaded with an army of about 36,000 and forced the Bey of Tunis, Muhammad III as-Sadiq, to agree to the terms of the 1881 Treaty of Bardo.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] With this treaty, Tunisia was officially made a French protectorate, over the objections of Italy.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] European settlements in the country were actively encouraged; the number of French colonists grew from 34,000 in 1906 to 144,000 in 1945.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In 1910 there were also 105,000 Italians in Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] During the Second World War, the protectorate of Tunisia was controlled by the collaborationist Vichy government in Metropolitan France.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The antisemitic Statute on Jews enacted by the Vichy government was also implemented in Vichy-controlled Northwest Africa and other overseas French territories.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Thus, the persecution and murder of the Jews from 1940 to 1943 was part of the Holocaust in France.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] From November 1942 until May 1943, Vichy-controlled Tunisia was occupied by Germany.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] SS Commander Walter Rauff continued to implement the "Final Solution" there.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] From 1942 to 1943, Tunisia was the scene of the Tunisia Campaign, a series of battles between the Axis and Allied forces.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The battle opened with initial success by the German and Italian forces, but the massive supply and numerical superiority of the Allies led to the Axis surrender on 13 May 1943.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The six-month campaign of Tunisia's liberation from Axis occupation signalled the end of the war in Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] After the liberation of Tunisia from the Germans, the French regained control over the government and made participation in a nationalist party illegal once more.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Moncef Bey, who was popular amongst Tunisians, was deposed by the French.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The French claimed that his removal was due to him being sympathetic to the Axis countries during German occupation, but the real reason is up for debate.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In 1945 after escaping French surveillance, Tunisian nationalist Habib Bourguiba arrived in Cairo.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] While there, he was able to make contact with the Arab League.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Later in 1946, after traveling to other Middle Eastern countries, he made his way to the United States to speak to both the United Nations at their headquarters at Lake Success and U.S.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] State Department officials in Washington D.C., pleading the case of the Tunisian nationalists.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] As part of postwar Tunisia, a new all-Tunisian labor organization was formed, the Union Générale des Travailleurs (UGTT).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] This was one of the stronger components of the nationalist group Neo-Destour.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Habib Bourguiba made his way to the United States on 13 September 1949.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] He attended the American Federation of Labor meeting in San Francisco, California.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The French were opposed to his presence there, and the US feared political change in North Africa due to the looming presence of possible Soviet Union communist expansion.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Bourguiba continued to plead to foreign leaders when he traveled to Italy on 6 November 1951.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] His contacts included Alberto Mellini Ponce De León, Mario Toscano, and Licinio Vestri.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] De León was an old friend of Bourguiba who had helped free him from German captivity, Toscano was the head of the *Ufficio Studi e Documentazione* in the Ministry of Foreign Affairs, and Vestri was an Africanist scholar.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Despite his best efforts, the Italians remained neutral as they did not want to ruin relations with NATO ally France, nor did they want to hamper any possibility of future relations with Tunisia as it served as a key part of the Mediterranean.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The French Resident General in Tunisia, Jean de Hautecloque left Tunis to go to Paris on 25 August 1953, when he was replaced by Pierre Voizard.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Voizard had previously been the French Minister to Monaco.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] A month after his arrival in Tunis on 26 September 1953, Voizard made many changes to ease tensions in Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] He lifted press censorship and freed several political prisoners.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] He also restored the full powers of civil authorities and raised the state of siege in the Sahel.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 26 January 1954, Voizard announced that there would soon be new reforms in favor of granting more sovereignty to Tunisians while insuring the interests of the French and French citizens in Tunisia, at the Cercle Republicain d'outre Mer in Paris.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Neo-Destour group was not in favor of these reforms if they themselves were not involved in their creation.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] They also demanded the freedom of Bourguiba who was imprisoned on the Isle of Galete.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia achieved independence from France on 20 March 1956 with Habib Bourguiba as Prime Minister.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] 20 March is celebrated annually as Tunisian Independence Day.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] A year later, Tunisia was declared a republic, with Bourguiba as the first President.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] From independence in 1956 until the 2011 revolution, the government and the Constitutional Democratic Rally (RCD), formerly Neo Destour and the Socialist Destourian Party, were effectively one.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Following a report by Amnesty International, *The Guardian* called Tunisia "one of the most modern but repressive countries in the Arab world".
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 12 May 1964, Tunisia nationalized foreign farmlands.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Immediately after, France canceled all financial assistance for the country, which was to amount to more than $40 million.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] This led to the Tunisian National Assembly passing a bill that required all residents of the country to subscribe to a "popular loan" in proportion to their income.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] From 1977 until 2005, Tunisia was a shooting location for five films of the *Star Wars* film franchise.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In 1982, Tunisia became the center of the Palestine Liberation Organization, based in the capital Tunis.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 1 October 1985, the Israeli Air Force bombed the PLO Headquarters, killing at least 60 people.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In November 1987, doctors declared Bourguiba unfit to rule and, in a bloodless coup d'état, Prime Minister Zine El Abidine Ben Ali assumed the presidency in accordance with Article 57 of the Tunisian constitution.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The anniversary of Ben Ali's succession, 7 November, was celebrated as a national holiday.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] He was consistently re-elected with enormous majorities every five years (well over 80 percent of the vote), the last being 25 October 2009, until he fled the country amid popular unrest in January 2011.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Ben Ali and his family were accused of corruption and plundering the country's money.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Economic liberalisation provided further opportunities for financial mismanagement, while corrupt members of the Trabelsi family, most notably in the cases of Imed Trabelsi and Belhassen Trabelsi, controlled much of the business sector in the country.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The First Lady Leila Ben Ali was described as an "unabashed shopaholic" who used the state airplane to make frequent unofficial trips to Europe's fashion capitals.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia refused a French request for the extradition of two of the President's nephews, from Leila's side, who were accused by the French State prosecutor of having stolen two mega-yachts from a French marina.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] According to *Le Monde*, Ben Ali's son-in-law was being primed to eventually take over the country.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Independent human rights groups, such as Amnesty International, Freedom House, and Protection International, documented that basic human and political rights were not respected.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The regime obstructed in any way possible the work of local human rights organizations.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In 2008, in terms of press freedom, Tunisia was ranked 143rd out of 173.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Tunisian Revolution was an intensive campaign of civil resistance that was precipitated by high unemployment, food inflation, corruption, a lack of freedom of speech and other political freedoms and poor living conditions.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Labour unions were said to be an integral part of the protests.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The protests inspired the Arab Spring, a wave of similar actions throughout the Arab world.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The catalyst for mass demonstrations was the death of Mohamed Bouazizi, a 26-year-old Tunisian street vendor, who set himself afire on 17 December 2010 in protest at the confiscation of his wares and the humiliation inflicted on him by a municipal official named Faida Hamdy.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Anger and violence intensified following Bouazizi's death on 4 January 2011, ultimately leading longtime President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali to resign and flee the country on 14 January 2011, after 23 years in power.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Protests continued for banning of the ruling party and the eviction of all its members from the transitional government formed by Mohammed Ghannouchi.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Eventually the new government gave in to the demands.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] A Tunis court banned the ex-ruling party RCD and confiscated all its resources.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] A decree by the minister of the interior banned the "political police", special forces which were used to intimidate and persecute political activists.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 3 March 2011, the interim president announced that elections to a Constituent Assembly would be held on 24 July 2011.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 9 June 2011, the prime minister announced the election would be postponed until 23 October 2011.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] International and internal observers declared the vote free and fair.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Ennahda Movement, formerly banned under the Ben Ali regime, came out of the election as the largest party, with 89 seats out of a total of 217.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 12 December 2011, former dissident and veteran human rights activist Moncef Marzouki was elected president.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In March 2012, Ennahda declared it will not support making sharia the main source of legislation in the new constitution, maintaining the secular nature of the state.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Ennahda's stance on the issue was criticized by hardline Islamists, who wanted strict sharia, but was welcomed by secular parties.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 6 February 2013, Chokri Belaid, the leader of the leftist opposition and prominent critic of Ennahda, was assassinated.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In 2014, President Moncef Marzouki established Tunisia's Truth and Dignity Commission, as a key part of creating a national reconciliation.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia was hit by two terror attacks on foreign tourists in 2015, first killing 22 people at the Bardo National Museum, and later killing 38 people at the Sousse beachfront.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisian president Beji Caid Essebsi renewed the state of emergency in October for three more months.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Tunisian National Dialogue Quartet won the 2015 Nobel Peace Prize for its work in building a peaceful, pluralistic political order in Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia's first democratically elected president Beji Caid Essebsi died in July 2019.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Following him, Kais Saied became Tunisia's president after a landslide victory in the 2019 Tunisian presidential elections in October.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 23 October 2019, Saied was sworn in as Tunisia's new president.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 25 July 2021, amid ongoing demonstrations concerning government dysfunction and corruption and rises in COVID-19 cases, Kais Saied unilaterally suspended parliament, dismissed the prime minister and withdrew immunity of parliament members.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In September 2021, Saied said he would appoint a committee to help draft new constitutional amendments.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 29 September, he named Najla Bouden as the new prime minister and tasked her with forming a cabinet, which was sworn in on 11 October.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 3 February 2022, Tunisia was voted to the African Union's (AU) Peace and Security Council for the term 2022–2024, according to the Tunisian Foreign Ministry.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The poll took place on the fringes of the AU Executive Council's 40th ordinary session, which was held in the Ethiopian capital of Addis Ababa, according to the ministry.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In February 2022, Tunisia and the International Monetary Fund held preliminary negotiations in the hopes of securing a multibillion-dollar bailout for an economy beset by recession, public debt, inflation, and unemployment.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In April 2023, the Tunisian government closed the headquarters of the Ennahda party and arrested its leader Rached Ghannouchi.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In October 2023 Abir Moussi, head of the Free Destourian Party (FDL), became the latest prominent opponent of president Saied to have been detained or imprisoned.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The FDL had emerged from the Democratic Constitutional Assembly.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In September 2023 Saied had asked to postpone a visit by a delegation of the EU commission to discuss migration according to Minister of the Interior Kamel Feki.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Meanwhile, human rights organisations were criticizing the July migration agreement.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Feki said that Tunisia, which is one of the most important transit countries for people on their way to Europe, cannot act as a border guard for other countries.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In October 2023 Saied turned down 127 million in EU aid saying that the amount was small and doesn't square with a deal signed three months ago.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] This in turn caused surprise in Brussels.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In April 2025, Tunisia dismantled dozens of makeshift camps housing African migrants, displacing as many as 7,000 people.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 6 October 2024, President Kais Saied won a second term with more than 90% of the vote in a presidential election with a 28.8% turnout.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Five political parties had urged people to boycott the elections.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia is situated on the Mediterranean coast of Northwest Africa, midway between the Atlantic Ocean and the Nile Delta.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] It is bordered by Algeria on the west (965 km) and southwest and Libya on the south east (459 km).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] It lies between latitudes 30° and 38°N, and longitudes 7° and 12°E.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] An abrupt southward turn of the Mediterranean coast in northern Tunisia gives the country two distinctive Mediterranean coasts, west–east in the north, and north–south in the east.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Though it is relatively small in size, Tunisia has great environmental diversity due to its north–south extent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Differences in Tunisia, like the rest of the Maghreb, are largely north–south environmental differences defined by sharply decreasing rainfall southward from any point.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Dorsal, the eastern extension of the Atlas Mountains, runs across Tunisia in a northeasterly direction from the Algerian border in the west to the Cape Bon peninsula in the east.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] North of the Dorsal is the Tell, a region characterized by low, rolling hills and plains, again an extension of mountains to the west in Algeria.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In the Khroumerie, the northwestern corner of the Tunisian Tell, elevations reach 1,050 metres (3,440 ft) and snow occurs in winter.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Sahel, a broadening coastal plain along Tunisia's eastern Mediterranean coast, is among the world's premier areas of olive cultivation.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Inland from the Sahel, between the Dorsal and a range of hills south of Gafsa, are the Steppes.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Much of the southern region is semi-arid and desert.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia has a coastline 1,148 kilometres (713 mi) long.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In maritime terms, the country claims a contiguous zone of 24 nautical miles (44 kilometres), and a territorial sea of 12 nautical miles (22 kilometres).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The city of Tunis is built on a hill slope down to the lake of Tunis.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] These hills contain places such as Notre-Dame de Tunis, Ras Tabia, La Rabta, La Kasbah, Montfleury and La Manoubia with altitudes just above 50 metres (160 feet).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The city is located at the crossroads of a narrow strip of land between Lake Tunis and Séjoumi.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia's climate is Mediterranean in the north, with mild rainy winters and hot, dry summers.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The terrain in the north is mountainous, which, moving south, gives way to a hot, dry central plain.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The south is semiarid, and merges into the Sahara.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] A series of salt lakes, known as *chotts* or *shatts*, lie in an east–west line at the northern edge of the Sahara, extending from the Gulf of Gabes into Algeria.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The lowest point is Chott el Djerid at 17 metres (56 ft) below sea level and the highest is Jebel ech Chambi at 1,544 metres (5,066 ft).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia is home to five terrestrial ecoregions: Mediterranean conifer and mixed forests, Saharan halophytics, Mediterranean dry woodlands and steppe, Mediterranean woodlands and forests, and North Saharan steppe and woodlands.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia is a presidential republic with a president serving as head of state, a prime minister as head of government, a bicameral parliament, and a civil law court system.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Constitution of Tunisia, adopted 26 January 2014, guarantees rights for women and states that the President's religion "shall be Islam".
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In October 2014 Tunisia held its first elections under the new constitution following the Arab Spring.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia was the only democracy in North Africa until 2021.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] After a democratic backsliding, the country now classifies as "hybrid regime" in the Democracy Index (The Economist).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Between 2020 and 2022 the V-Dem Democracy indices score for electoral democracy dropped from 0.727 to 0.307.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] After the 2022 constitutional referendum, Tunisia became a unitary presidential republic.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The number of legalized political parties in Tunisia has grown considerably since the revolution.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] There are now over 100 legal parties, including several that existed under the former regime.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] During the rule of Ben Ali, only three functioned as independent opposition parties: the PDP, FDTL, and Tajdid.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] While some older parties are well-established and can draw on previous party structures, many of the 100-plus parties extant as of February 2012 are small.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Rare for the Arab world, women held more than 20% of seats in the country's pre-revolution bicameral parliament.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In the 2011 constituent assembly, women held between 24% and 31% of all seats.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia is included in the European Union's European Neighbourhood Policy (ENP), which aims at bringing the EU and its neighbours closer.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 23 November 2014, Tunisia held its first presidential election following the Arab Spring in 2011.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Tunisian legal system is heavily influenced by French civil law, while the law of personal status is based on Islamic law.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] A Code of Personal Status was adopted shortly after independence in 1956, which, among other things, gave women full legal status (allowing them to run and own businesses, have bank accounts, and seek passports under their own authority).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The code outlawed the practices of polygamy and repudiation and a husband's right to unilaterally divorce his wife.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Further reforms in 1993 included a provision to allow Tunisian women to transmit citizenship even if they are married to a foreigner and living abroad.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Law of Personal Status is applied to all Tunisians regardless of their religion.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Code of Personal Status remains one of the most progressive civil codes in North Africa and the Muslim world.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] On 25 May 2022, President Kais Saied issued a decree for change of constitution by 25 July.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The referendum was held that day to a low turnout of 30% of voters, the overwhelming majority of whom accepted the new constitution, strengthening significantly the presidential powers.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Maghreb countries have toughened their tone towards Europe recently.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia maintains diplomatic relations with over 160+ countries.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Former President Zine El Abidine Ben Ali has maintained its long-time policy of seeking good relations with the West, while playing an active role in Arab and African regional bodies.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] President Habib Bourguiba took a nonaligned stance but emphasized close relations with the European Union, Pakistan, and the United States.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] As of 2008, Tunisia had an army of 27,000 personnel equipped with 84 main battle tanks and 48 light tanks.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The navy had 4,800 personnel operating 25 patrol boats and 6 other craft.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Tunisian Air Force has 154 aircraft and 4 UAVs.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Paramilitary forces consisted of a 12,000-member national guard.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia's military spending was 1.6% of GDP as of 2006.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The army is responsible for national defence and also internal security.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia has participated in peacekeeping efforts in the DROC and Ethiopia/Eritrea.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] United Nations peacekeeping deployments for the Tunisian armed forces have been in Cambodia (UNTAC), Namibia (UNTAG), Somalia, Rwanda, Burundi, Western Sahara (MINURSO) and the 1960s mission in the Congo, ONUC.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The military has historically played a professional, apolitical role in defending the country from external threats.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Since January 2011 and at the direction of the executive branch, the military has taken on increasing responsibility for domestic security and humanitarian crisis response.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia is the 73rd most peaceful country in the world, according to the 2024 Global Peace Index.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia is subdivided into 24 governorates (*Wilaya*), which are further divided into 264 "delegations" or "districts" (*mutamadiyat*), and further subdivided into municipalities (*baladiyats*) and sectors (*imadats*).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia's Penal Code criminalises several forms of corruption, including active and passive bribery, abuse of office, extortion and conflicts of interest, but the anti-corruption framework is not effectively enforced.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] However, according to the Corruption Perceptions Index published annually by Transparency International, Tunisia was ranked the least corrupt North African country in 2016, with a score of 41.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia has a diverse economy, ranging from agriculture, mining, manufacturing, and petroleum products, to tourism, which accounted for 7% of the total GDP and 370,000 jobs in 2009.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In 2008 it had an economy of US$41 billion in nominal terms, and $82 billion in PPP.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The agricultural sector accounts for 11.6% of the GDP, industry 25.7%, and services 62.8%.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The industrial sector is mainly made up of clothing and footwear manufacturing, production of car parts, and electric machinery.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Although Tunisia managed an average 5% growth over the last decade, it continues to suffer from a high unemployment rate, especially among youth.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The European Union remains Tunisia's first trading partner, currently accounting for 72.5% of Tunisian imports and 75% of Tunisian exports.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia is one of the European Union's most established trading partners in the Mediterranean region and ranks as the EU's 30th largest trading partner.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia was the first Mediterranean country to sign an Association Agreement with the European Union, in July 1995, although even before the date of entry came into force, Tunisia started dismantling tariffs on bilateral EU trade.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia finalised the tariffs dismantling for industrial products in 2008 and therefore was the first non-EU Mediterranean country to enter in a free trade area with the EU.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The consequences of the Russian invasion of Ukraine for the global food supply are being felt particularly strongly in Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In June 2023 the World Bank Group lent Tunisia $268.4 million to finance ELMED, an electrical interconnection project with Italy to import electricity generated from renewable energy sources to Sicily and the EU via a 600 Megawatt undersea cable.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia was ranked 76th in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Among Tunisia's tourist attractions are its cosmopolitan capital city of Tunis, the ancient ruins of Carthage, the Muslim and Jewish quarters of Djerba, coastal resorts outside of Monastir, and the night life-driven city of Hammamet.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] According to *The New York Times*, Tunisia is "known for its golden beaches, sunny weather and affordable luxuries".
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia's current power production capacity is estimated at 5,944 MW installed in 25 power plants as of 2024.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] State owned power utility company STEG (Société Tunisienne d'Electricité et de Gas) controls 92.1% of the country's installed power production capacity and produces 83.5% of the electricity.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Oil production began in 1966 in Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The production rate of crude oil in Tunisia was 29,200 barrels per day (4,640 m3/d) at the end of September 2024.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia had plans for two nuclear power stations, to be operational by 2020.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Both facilities are projected to produce 900–1000 MW.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] France is set to become an important partner in Tunisia's nuclear power plans, having signed an agreement, along with other partners, to deliver training and technology.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] As of 2015, Tunisia has abandoned these plans.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Instead, Tunisia is considering other options to diversify its energy mix, such as renewable energies, coal, shale gas, liquified natural gas and constructing a submarine power interconnection with Italy.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The country maintains 19,232 kilometres (11,950 mi) of roads, with three highways: the A1 from Tunis to Sfax (works ongoing for Sfax-Libya), A3 Tunis-Beja (works ongoing Beja – Boussalem, studies ongoing Boussalem – Algeria) and A4 Tunis – Bizerte.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] There are 29 airports in Tunisia, with Tunis Carthage International Airport and Djerba–Zarzis International Airport being the most important ones.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] A new airport, Enfidha – Hammamet International Airport opened in 2011.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The airport is located north of Sousse at Enfidha and is to mainly serve the resorts of Hamammet and Port El Kantaoui, together with inland cities such as Kairouan.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Five airlines are headquartered in Tunisia: Tunisair, Syphax Airlines, Karthago Airlines, Nouvelair, and Tunisair Express.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The railway network is operated by SNCFT and amounts to 2,135 kilometres (1,327 mi) in total.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The Tunis area is served by a Light rail network named *Metro Leger* which is managed by Transtu.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia has achieved the highest access rates to water supply and sanitation services in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] As of 2011, access to safe drinking water became close to universal approaching 100% in urban areas and 90% in rural areas.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Tunisia provides good quality drinking water throughout the year.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Responsibility for the water supply systems in urban areas and large rural centers is assigned to the *Sociéte Nationale d'Exploitation et de Distribution des Eaux* (SONEDE), a national water supply authority that is an autonomous public entity under the Ministry of Agriculture.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Planning, design, and supervision of small and medium water supplies in the remaining rural areas are the responsibility of the *Direction Générale du Génie Rurale* (DGGR).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] In 1974, ONAS was established to manage the sanitation sector.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] Since 1993, ONAS has had the status of a main operator for the protection of the water environment and combating pollution.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p01] The rate of non-revenue water is the lowest in the region at 21% in 2012.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] According to the CIA, as of 2021, Tunisia has a population of 11,811,335 inhabitants.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The government has supported a successful family planning program that has reduced the population growth rate to just over 1% per annum, contributing to Tunisia's economic and social stability.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The first people known to history in what is now Tunisia were the Berbers.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Numerous civilizations and peoples have invaded, migrated to, or have been assimilated into the population over the millennia, with influences of population from Phoenicians/Carthaginians, Romans, Vandals, Arabs, Spaniards, Ottoman Turks and Janissaries, and French.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] There was a continuing inflow of nomadic Arab tribes from the Arabian Peninsula.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Black Tunisians are mostly descended from sub-Saharan Africans brought to Tunisia as part of the slave trade.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Amazighs are generally concentrated in the Dahar mountains and on the island of Djerba in the southeast, and in the Khroumire mountainous region in the north-west.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] An important number of genetic and other historical studies point to the predominance of the Amazighs in Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] An Ottoman influence has been particularly significant in forming the Turco-Tunisian community.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Other peoples have also migrated to Tunisia during different time periods, including West Africans, Greeks, Romans, Vandals, Phoenicians (Punics), Jews, and French and Italians.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] By 1870, the distinction between the Arabic-speaking population and the Turkish elite had blurred.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] After the Reconquista and expulsion of non-Christians and Moriscos from Spain, many Spanish Muslims and Jews arrived in Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] From the late 19th century to the period after World War II, Tunisia was home to large populations of French and Italians (255,000 Europeans in 1956), although nearly all of them, along with the Jewish population, left after Tunisia became independent.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The history of the Jews in Tunisia goes back some 2,000 years.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In 1948, the Jewish population was estimated at 105,000, but by 2013 only about 1000 remained.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Arabic is the official language of Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Tunisian Arabic, known as Tounsi, is the national, vernacular variety of Arabic used by the public.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] There is also a small minority of speakers of Berber languages known collectively as Jebbali or Shelha in the country.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Actively spoken Berber languages are Jerba Berber on the island of Djerba and Matmata Berber in the city of Matmata.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Speakers of Berber dialects were 2% of the population. .
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] French also plays a major role in Tunisian society, despite having no official status.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] It is widely used in education (e.g., as the language of instruction in the sciences in secondary school), the press, and business.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In 2022, there were 6,321,000 French-speakers in Tunisia, or about 52% of the population.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Italian is understood and spoken by a small part of the Tunisian population.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Shop signs, menus and road signs in Tunisia are generally written in both Arabic and French.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Tunisia's constitution declares Islam as the official state religion—and the absolute majority of its population, or around 98%, report to be Muslims, while some 2% follow predominantly Christianity or Judaism.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] According to a 2018 survey conducted by the Arab Barometer, the vast majority of Tunisians (99.4%) continue to identify as Muslim.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The survey also found that more than one third of Tunisians identify as non-religious.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The percentage of Tunisians identifying themselves as non-religious has recently increased from around 12% in 2013 to around 33% in 2018, making Tunisia the least religious country in the Arab world.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Nearly half of young Tunisians described themselves as non-religious, according to that same survey.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] However, as of July 2022, new surveys by the Arab Barometer say otherwise, particularly BBC's programme, *The Newsroom* journalists highlighting that the previously noted wave of those saying they were not religious has been, in fact, "reversed".
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The most recent 2021 Arab Barometer survey reported that 44% of Tunisians consider themselves religious, 37% somewhat religious, and 19% non-religious.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Tunisians enjoy a significant degree of religious freedom, a right enshrined and protected in its constitution, which guarantees the freedom of thoughts, beliefs and to practice one's religion.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The country has a secular culture where religion is separated from not only political, but also public life.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Individual Tunisians are tolerant of religious freedom and generally do not inquire about a person's personal beliefs.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The bulk of Tunisians belong to the Maliki school of Sunni Islam, and their mosques are easily recognizable by square minarets.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] However, the Turks brought with them the teaching of the Hanafi school during Ottoman rule, which still survives among families of Turkish descent today; their mosques traditionally have octagonal minarets.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Sunnis form the majority, with non-denominational Muslims being the second largest group of Muslims, followed by Ibadite Amazighs.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The Church of Carthage, in particular, became significant in the history of Christianity, playing a key role in the development of Christian philosophy and theology, and producing many prominent religious scholars and theologians.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Prior to independence, Tunisia was home to more than 250,000 Christians (mostly of Italian and Maltese ancestry).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Many Christian Italian settlers left to Italy or France after independence from France.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Today, Tunisia's sizable Christian community of something over 35,000 is composed mainly of Catholics (22,000), and to a lesser degree Protestants.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Berber Christians continued to live in some Nefzaoua villages up until the early fifteenth century, and the community of Tunisian Christians existed in the town of Tozeur up to the 18th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The International Religious Freedom Report for 2007 estimates that thousands of Tunisian Muslims have converted to Christianity.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Judaism is the third largest religion, with between 1,000 and 1,400 members.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] One third of the Jewish population lives in and around the capital.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The remainder lives on the island of Djerba with 39 synagogues where the Jewish community dates back 2,600 years, in Sfax, and in Hammam-Lif.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Djerba, an island in the Gulf of Gabès, is home to El Ghriba synagogue, which is one of the oldest synagogues in the world and the oldest continuously used.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Many Jews consider it a pilgrimage site, with celebrations taking place there once a year due to its age and the legend that the synagogue was built using stones from Solomon's Temple.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Although antisemitic violence has been reported, Tunisia and Morocco are said to be the Arab countries most accepting of their Jewish populations.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The total adult literacy rate in 2008 was 78% and this rate goes up to 97.3% when considering only people from 15 to 24 years old.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Education is given a high priority and accounts for 6% of GNP.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] A basic education for children between the ages of 6 and 16 has been compulsory since 1991.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Tunisia ranked 17th in the category of "quality of the [higher] educational system" and 21st in the category of "quality of primary education" in The Global Competitiveness Report 2008–09, released by the World Economic Forum.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] While children generally acquire Tunisian Arabic at home, when they enter school at age six, they are taught to read and write in Standard Arabic.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] From the age of 8, they are taught French while English is introduced at the age of 11.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The four years of secondary education are open to all holders of Diplôme de Fin d'Études de l'Enseignement de Base where the students focus on entering university level or join the workforce after completion.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The Enseignement secondaire is divided into two stages: general academic and specialized.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The higher education system in Tunisia has experienced a rapid expansion and the number of students has more than tripled over the past 10 years from approximately 102,000 in 1995 to 365,000 in 2005.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The gross enrollment rate at the tertiary level in 2007 was 31 percent, with gender parity index of GER of 1.5.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In 2010, spending on healthcare accounted for 3.37% of the country's GDP.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The life expectancy at birth was 75.73 years in 2016, or 73.72 years for males and 77.78 years for females.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The culture of Tunisia is mixed due to its long established history of outside influence from people – such as Phoenicians, Romans, Vandals, Byzantines, Arabs, Siculo-Normans, Turks, Italians, Maltese and the French – who all left their mark on the country.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The birth of Tunisian contemporary painting is strongly linked to the School of Tunis, established by a group of artists from Tunisia united by the desire to incorporate native themes and rejecting the influence of Orientalist colonial painting.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] It was founded in 1949 and brings together French and Tunisian Muslims, Christians and Jews.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Pierre Boucherle was its main instigator, along with Yahia Turki, Abdelaziz Gorgi, Moses Levy, Ammar Farhat, and Jules Lellouche.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Given its doctrine, some members have therefore turned to the sources of aesthetic Arab-Muslim art, such as miniature Islamic architecture, etc.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Expressionist paintings by Amara Debbache, Jellal Ben Abdallah, and Ali Ben Salem are recognized while abstract art captures the imagination of painters like Edgar Naccache, Nello Levy, and Hedi Turki.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] After independence in 1956, the art movement in Tunisia was propelled by the dynamics of nation building and by artists serving the state.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] A Ministry of Culture was established, under the leadership of ministers such as Habib Boularès who oversaw art and education and power.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Artists gained international recognition such as Hatem El Mekki or Zoubeir Turki and influenced a generation of new young painters.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Sadok Gmech draws his inspiration from national wealth while Moncef Ben Amor turns to fantasy.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In another development, Youssef Rekik reused the technique of painting on glass and founded Nja Mahdaoui calligraphy with its mystical dimension.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] There are currently fifty art galleries housing exhibitions of Tunisian and international artists.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] These galleries include Gallery Yahia in Tunis and Carthage Essaadi gallery.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] A new exposition opened in an old monarchal palace in Bardo dubbed the "awakening of a nation".
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The exposition boasts documents and artifacts from the Tunisian reformist monarchial rule in mid-19th century.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Tunisian literature exists in two forms: Arabic and French.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Arabic literature dates back to the 7th century with the arrival of Arab civilization in the region.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] It is more important in both volume and value than French literature, which was introduced during the French protectorate from 1881.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] As for poetry, Tunisian poetry typically opts for nonconformity and innovation with poets such as Aboul-Qacem Echebbi.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] As for literature in French, it is characterized by its critical approach.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Contrary to the pessimism of Albert Memmi, who predicted that Tunisian literature was sentenced to die young, a high number of Tunisian writers are abroad including Abdelwahab Meddeb, Bakri Tahar, Mustapha Tlili, Hele Beji, or Mellah Fawzi.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Themes of wandering, exile, heartbreak, disconnection, memory, and representation are often focuses of Tunisian literature.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The national bibliography lists 1249 non-school books published in 2002 in Tunisia, with 885 titles in Arabic.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Nearly a third of the books are published for children.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In 1930 The Rachidia was founded, well known thanks to artists from the Jewish community.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The founding in 1934 of a musical school helped revive Arab Andalusian music largely to a social and cultural revival led by the elite of the time who became aware of the risks of loss of the musical heritage and which they believed threatened the foundations of Tunisian national identity.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The institution did not take long to assemble a group of musicians, poets, scholars.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The creation of Radio Tunis in 1938 allowed musicians a greater opportunity to disseminate their works, with the station employing a policy of promoting Tunisian musicians exclusively.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Notable Tunisian musicians include Saber Rebaï, Dhafer Youssef, Belgacem Bouguenna, Sonia M'barek, Latifa, Salah El Mahdi, Anouar Brahem, Emel Mathlouthi and Lotfi Bouchnak.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Hundreds of international festivals, national, regional or local punctuate the calendar year.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Music and theatrical festivals dominate the national cultural scene.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Several festivals take place annually in summer: the International Festival of Carthage in July, the International Festival of Arts of Mahr from late July to early August, and the International Festival of Hammamet in July and August.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The Carthage Film Festival is held in October and November of every other year, alternating with the Carthage Theatre Festival.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] It was created in 1966 by the Tunisian Minister of Culture to showcase films from the Maghreb, Africa and the Middle East.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In order to be eligible for the competition, a film must have a director of African or Middle Eastern nationality, and have been produced at least two years before entry.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The grand prize is the *Tanit d'or*, or "Golden Tanit", named for the lunar goddess of ancient Carthage; the award is in the shape of her symbol, a trapezium surmounted by a horizontal line and a circle.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The International Festival of the Sahara, celebrated annually at the end of December, honors the cultural traditions associated with the Tunisian desert.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] This attracts many tourists and musicians from all around the world, as well as horsemen who flaunt their saddles and local fabrics and skills.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] There are also a number of musical festivals; some honor traditional Tunisian music, while others, including the Tabarka Jazz Festival, focus on other genres.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In the city of Sousse, the Carnival of Awussu is an annual festive and cultural event that unfolds each 24 July.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] It is a parade of symbolic chariots, fanfares and folk groups from Tunisia and elsewhere which takes place near the beach of Boujaafar, at the eve of the beginning of '*Awussu* (the word designating the heat wave of the month of August according to the Berber calendar).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Originally it was a Pagan feast (Neptunalia) celebrating the god of the seas, Neptune in the Roman province of Africa, and might even go back to Phoenician times: the appellation Awussu is a possible deformation of Oceanus.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Omek Tannou is an ancient Tunisian rainmaking festival which was inherited from Punic and Berber traditions involving invocations of the goddess Tanit.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] This song varies according to the region because the term *shta* designates rain only in certain urban areas.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Each housewife then pours a little water on the statuette, invoking rain.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The TV media has long remained under the domination of the Establishment of the Broadcasting Authority Tunisia (ERTT) and its predecessor, the Tunisian Radio and Television, founded in 1957.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] On 7 November 2006, President Zine el-Abidine Ben Ali announced the demerger of the business into two separate companies, which became effective on 31 August 2007.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Most programs are in Arabic, but some are in French.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Growth in private sector radio and television broadcasting has seen the creation of numerous operations including Radio Mosaique FM, Jawhara FM, Zaytuna FM, Hannibal TV, Ettounsiya TV, and Nessma TV.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In 2007, some 245 newspapers and magazines (compared to only 91 in 1987) are 90% owned by private groups and independents.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The Tunisian political parties have the right to publish their own newspapers, but those of the opposition parties have very limited editions (like Al Mawkif or Mouwatinoun).
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Before the recent democratic transition, although freedom of the press was formally guaranteed by the constitution, almost all newspapers have in practice followed the government line report.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Critical approach to the activities of the president, government and the Constitutional Democratic Rally Party (then in power) were suppressed.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In essence, the media was dominated by state authorities through the Agence Tunis Afrique Presse.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] This has changed since, as the media censorship by the authorities have been largely abolished, and self-censorship has significantly decreased.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Nonetheless, the current regulatory framework and social and political culture mean that the future of press and media freedom is still unclear.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In September 2022 Tunisian president Kais Saied signed Decree Law 54, which purported to combat "false information and rumours" on the Internet.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Article 24 of the decree gives up to five years imprisonment and a fine of up to 50,000 dinar for anyone found to be spreading such information.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] This is doubled if the offending statement is made about a state official.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Football is the most popular sport in Tunisia.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The Tunisia national football team, also known as "The Eagles of Carthage", won the 2004 African Cup of Nations (ACN) as hosts.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] They also represented Africa in the 2005 FIFA Cup of Confederations, which was held in Germany, but they could not go beyond the first round.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Their premier football league is the Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The main clubs are Espérance Sportive de Tunis, Étoile Sportive du Sahel, Club Africain, Club Sportif Sfaxien, Union Sportive Monastirienne, Stade Tunisien, and CA Bizertin.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The Tunisia men's national handball team has participated in several handball world championships.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The national league consists of about 12 teams, with Club Africain and Espérance dominating.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The most famous Tunisian handball player is Wissem Hmam.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In the 2005 Handball Championship in Tunis, Wissem Hmam was ranked as the top scorer of the tournament.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The Tunisian national handball team won the African Cup ten times, being the team dominating this competition.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The Tunisians won the 2018 African Cup in Gabon by defeating Egypt.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Tunisia's national basketball team has emerged as a top side in Africa.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] The team won the 2011 Afrobasket and hosted Africa's top basketball event in 1965, 1987 and 2015.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Tunisia was one of the continent's pioneers in basketball as it established one of Africa's first competitive leagues.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In boxing, Victor "Young" Perez was world champion in the flyweight weight class in 1931 and 1932.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In the 2008 Summer Olympics, Tunisian Oussama Mellouli won a gold medal in 1500 meter freestyle.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In the 2012 Summer Olympics, he won a bronze medal in the 1500 meter freestyle and a gold medal in the men's marathon swim at a distance of 10 kilometers.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] In 2012, Tunisia participated for the seventh time in its history in the Summer Paralympic Games.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Their national team finished the competition with 19 medals; 9 golds, 5 silvers and 5 bronzes.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Tunisia was classified 14th on the Paralympics medal table and 5th in Athletics.
[src:2023-african-beach-games/tunisia-p02] Throughout the years 2021 to 2023, tennis saw a spike of popularity in Tunisia and other Arabic countries as tennis player Ons Jabeur rapidly moved up the rankings reaching a career high ranking of number 3, and making 3 grand slam finals, including 2 at Wimbledon.
